WEBVTT

1
00:00:24.149 --> 00:00:26.526
(soap opera music playing)

2
00:00:46.671 --> 00:00:48.631
It doesn't make sense. I don't understand

3
00:00:48.715 --> 00:00:50.467
how something like this happened.

4
00:00:52.385 --> 00:00:53.928
I don't know what I'm gonna do.

5
00:00:54.095 --> 00:00:55.930
This has been my whole life,
and now it's gone.

6
00:00:55.972 --> 00:00:57.849
I don't know what I'm supposed to do.

7
00:00:59.017 --> 00:01:02.020
Pendleton Industries is all I've ever known.

8
00:01:02.187 --> 00:01:04.522
And now it's all been taken away.

9
00:01:06.399 --> 00:01:08.109
DANICA: When someone
sees a weakness in me,

10
00:01:08.193 --> 00:01:10.612
I turn that weakness into a strength.

11
00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:14.991
(gasps)

12
00:01:16.284 --> 00:01:18.286
Danica, you're so strong.

13
00:01:20.038 --> 00:01:22.791
I don't think I could do
anything like this.

14
00:01:23.708 --> 00:01:25.668
You can imagine changing your life...

15
00:01:25.835 --> 00:01:28.338
by fighting for the deed
to the land, Clarinda.

16
00:01:28.505 --> 00:01:32.425
Which is only possible if Bartholomew
is no longer living.

17
00:01:32.509 --> 00:01:33.802
(door opens)

18
00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:38.681
You will never get
the deed to the land again.

19
00:01:38.848 --> 00:01:40.767
I will never allow it.

20
00:01:40.934 --> 00:01:43.269
Put down that gun,
you silly girl.

21
00:01:43.978 --> 00:01:46.106
Watch your step, Bartholomew.

22
00:01:46.272 --> 00:01:47.982
Ridge is on his way.

23
00:01:48.149 --> 00:01:50.151
And he's still in love with Clarinda.

24
00:01:50.944 --> 00:01:53.154
And Jared loves me.

25
00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:54.948
Clarinda...

26
00:01:55.615 --> 00:01:56.950
it's true.

27
00:01:57.117 --> 00:01:58.201
I'm here for you.

28
00:02:08.128 --> 00:02:10.755
("I Feel Free" playing)

29
00:02:13.091 --> 00:02:18.596
MIMI: <i>This is the story of Joy,</i>
<i>as told by me, her grandmother.</i>

30
00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:27.730
<i>Everybody starts out with some kind</i>
<i>of dream of what life will be.</i>

31
00:02:31.943 --> 00:02:35.363
<i>Joy's dream started at this metal garage</i>
<i>her father ran.</i>

32
00:02:35.613 --> 00:02:37.907
(Young Joy humming)

33
00:02:44.247 --> 00:02:47.750
♪ Jackie, Jackie, bo-backie
Banana-fana, fo-fackie ♪

34
00:02:47.917 --> 00:02:49.711
♪ Fee-fi, mo-mackie
Jackie ♪

35
00:02:49.878 --> 00:02:53.381
MIMI: <i>My granddaughter</i>
<i>had a best friend, Jackie.</i>

36
00:02:53.548 --> 00:02:55.550
♪ Joy, Joy, bo-boy
Banana-fana, fo-foy ♪

37
00:02:55.717 --> 00:02:58.386
♪ While shivering in my shoes ♪

38
00:02:58.553 --> 00:03:00.555
♪ I strike a careless pose ♪

39
00:03:00.722 --> 00:03:02.557
MIMI: <i>A half-sister, Peggy.</i>

40
00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:06.561
<i>A dog.</i>

41
00:03:06.728 --> 00:03:08.771
It's okay. It's okay, Mitzy.

42
00:03:09.063 --> 00:03:10.481
MIMI: <i>A father.</i>

43
00:03:12.859 --> 00:03:14.652
<i>A mother...</i>

44
00:03:16.946 --> 00:03:18.740
<i>who is my daughter.</i>

45
00:03:20.116 --> 00:03:23.077
<i>A grandmother. That's me.</i>

46
00:03:30.710 --> 00:03:32.587
(classical music playing)

47
00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:39.093
<i>She made many beautiful things</i>
<i>in her room.</i>

48
00:03:39.260 --> 00:03:40.470
<i>Magic.</i>

49
00:03:41.763 --> 00:03:44.182
<i>Some people love to make things.</i>

50
00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:50.021
<i>They have the patience and the focus</i>
<i>to figure it out with their hands.</i>

51
00:03:50.188 --> 00:03:54.067
<i>Joy was one of those people</i>
<i>who rejoiced in making things.</i>

52
00:03:54.234 --> 00:03:58.238
And I open the gate
to the big green meadow.

53
00:03:58.905 --> 00:04:01.366
And I went into the forest.

54
00:04:02.116 --> 00:04:04.285
And there, I conquered many dangers.

55
00:04:06.079 --> 00:04:07.080
A wolf...

56
00:04:07.247 --> 00:04:09.415
and other scary things.

57
00:04:09.582 --> 00:04:12.627
And then I started to build
my very own house...

58
00:04:13.419 --> 00:04:14.420
where I would live...

59
00:04:14.587 --> 00:04:17.757
and make wonderful creations
for all the world...

60
00:04:17.924 --> 00:04:19.717
to see and have.

61
00:04:20.301 --> 00:04:21.761
And maybe for the prince and princess...

62
00:04:21.928 --> 00:04:24.514
who lived across the forest,
in the castle.

63
00:04:24.681 --> 00:04:25.682
See?

64
00:04:26.349 --> 00:04:28.101
And they were in love.

65
00:04:28.268 --> 00:04:29.769
And maybe they'd invite me over...

66
00:04:29.936 --> 00:04:31.813
because of the things that I made.

67
00:04:33.106 --> 00:04:34.816
YOUNG PEGGY: <i>You need</i>
<i>a handsome prince.</i>

68
00:04:34.899 --> 00:04:36.651
<i>That's what you need. A prince.</i>

69
00:04:38.695 --> 00:04:40.530
YOUNG JOY: <i>No, I don't need a prince.</i>

70
00:04:40.697 --> 00:04:43.783
<i>This is a special power.</i>
<i>I don't need a prince.</i>

71
00:04:46.744 --> 00:04:50.498
MIMI: <i>My daughter Terry is separated,</i>
<i>and alone in her room...</i>

72
00:04:50.665 --> 00:04:52.333
<i>watching soap operas.</i>

73
00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:53.710
DANICA: You can imagine
changing your life...

74
00:04:53.876 --> 00:04:56.796
by fighting for the deed
to the land, Clarinda.

75
00:04:57.714 --> 00:04:59.924
I have something for you.

76
00:05:00.091 --> 00:05:01.551
Oh, Danica...

77
00:05:02.593 --> 00:05:03.636
You're so strong.

78
00:05:03.803 --> 00:05:06.222
I don't think I could ever do
something like this.

79
00:05:10.476 --> 00:05:13.646
MIMI: <i>I always felt it was</i>
<i>for me to encourage her.</i>

80
00:05:14.939 --> 00:05:16.274
<i>So I said...</i>

81
00:05:16.816 --> 00:05:21.779
You are going to grow up and be a strong,
smart young woman...

82
00:05:21.988 --> 00:05:27.368
go to school, meet a fine young man,
have beautiful children of your own...

83
00:05:27.535 --> 00:05:32.999
and you're gonna build wonderful things
that you do in your room.

84
00:05:33.082 --> 00:05:34.083
Okay?

85
00:05:34.167 --> 00:05:36.586
<i>What happened to this girl's dreams?</i>

86
00:05:36.669 --> 00:05:37.879
(door closes)

87
00:05:37.962 --> 00:05:39.088
<i>Watch this.</i>

88
00:05:39.255 --> 00:05:41.257
Mother, I can't find my lanyard for work.

89
00:05:41.424 --> 00:05:43.593
They're not gonna let me through
airport security without it.

90
00:05:43.676 --> 00:05:45.053
Joy, you can't find your lanyard?

91
00:05:45.136 --> 00:05:47.221
-Can I help you?
-No, but I...

92
00:05:47.388 --> 00:05:48.473
Honey, listen.

93
00:05:48.639 --> 00:05:52.810
I know life hasn't gone as we discussed
many times, sweetheart.

94
00:05:52.977 --> 00:05:55.605
And you don't exactly have
your whole life ahead of you...

95
00:05:55.772 --> 00:05:58.524
but you still have a good portion
of it, anyway.

96
00:05:59.442 --> 00:06:01.486
Hope springs eternal.

97
00:06:02.695 --> 00:06:04.197
-Thanks, Mimi.
-Sure.

98
00:06:04.364 --> 00:06:06.949
Mother, look what I did find.

99
00:06:08.368 --> 00:06:09.786
What is that?

100
00:06:09.952 --> 00:06:11.829
How can you ask what this is?

101
00:06:12.455 --> 00:06:14.791
The dog collar I invented
in high school.

102
00:06:15.208 --> 00:06:17.043
Remember Mitzy choked a couple of times?

103
00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:19.587
So I invented a dog collar
with a quick release...

104
00:06:19.754 --> 00:06:20.838
so that a dog would never choke...

105
00:06:21.005 --> 00:06:24.592
and I covered it with reflective tape,
plus it's a flea collar.

106
00:06:24.759 --> 00:06:27.470
I probably wouldn't be late to this job
I'm going to...

107
00:06:27.637 --> 00:06:29.222
if you'd gotten me a patent or a lawyer.

108
00:06:29.389 --> 00:06:32.266
Joy the doer, Joy the doer.
You were always doing things, honey.

109
00:06:32.433 --> 00:06:34.685
How could I be expected
to remember everything?

110
00:06:34.852 --> 00:06:37.522
JOY: Now the Hartz company
has the patent to that collar.

111
00:06:37.688 --> 00:06:39.607
I don't know how to get a patent.

112
00:06:40.441 --> 00:06:41.901
What is that smell? (sniffs)

113
00:06:42.318 --> 00:06:44.946
Oh! How did you get
yogurt down here, Mother?

114
00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:47.657
TERRY: I was wondering
what that odor was.

115
00:06:47.824 --> 00:06:49.826
JOY: It's starting to mold for Pete's sake.

116
00:06:49.992 --> 00:06:54.080
Yes, I am, because I feel like I cannot
have the life bled out of me this way.

117
00:06:54.247 --> 00:06:57.083
Joy, look who's back.
Look who's back!

118
00:06:57.250 --> 00:06:58.793
Yes, Bartholomew is back.

119
00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:00.545
CLARINDA: No, no.

120
00:07:00.670 --> 00:07:01.838
I thought Bartholomew was dead?

121
00:07:02.004 --> 00:07:03.005
BARTHOLOMEW: And I'm a ghost.

122
00:07:03.172 --> 00:07:05.049
He came back as a ghost with
even greater powers.

123
00:07:05.216 --> 00:07:06.259
CLARINDA: Ghost, you go away!

124
00:07:06.426 --> 00:07:08.344
BARTHOLOMEW: My powers
are even greater now.

125
00:07:08.428 --> 00:07:10.555
CLARINDA: I cannot handle this.
How is this possible?

126
00:07:11.055 --> 00:07:12.056
RODERICK: Stay away from him.

127
00:07:12.223 --> 00:07:14.058
Clarinda, you don't know
what a ghost can do to you!

128
00:07:14.225 --> 00:07:15.643
BARTHOLOMEW:
Even from beyond the grave.

129
00:07:15.726 --> 00:07:16.978
-(doorbell rings)
-(knocking on door)

130
00:07:17.562 --> 00:07:19.230
Grandma's gonna take you
to the birthday party, okay?

131
00:07:19.397 --> 00:07:20.398
Five minutes.

132
00:07:21.941 --> 00:07:24.402
Hi. What are you doing here?

133
00:07:24.569 --> 00:07:26.779
I'm returning him to you.
I don't want him anymore.

134
00:07:26.946 --> 00:07:27.947
What?

135
00:07:28.531 --> 00:07:29.699
He's damaged.

136
00:07:29.866 --> 00:07:31.325
He has no place else to go.

137
00:07:31.742 --> 00:07:33.578
He's been living
in my house for two years.

138
00:07:33.744 --> 00:07:35.663
Oh, Dad, I'm so sorry.

139
00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:38.291
But you know,
Tony's living in the basement.

140
00:07:38.458 --> 00:07:40.460
Your ex-husband shouldn't be living
in your basement.

141
00:07:40.626 --> 00:07:42.462
That's not the proper way to be divorced.

142
00:07:42.628 --> 00:07:45.673
Okay. I don't know
where I'm gonna put you.

143
00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:47.592
Dad, don't go in there. Mom's in there.

144
00:07:47.675 --> 00:07:48.676
(gasps)

145
00:07:48.759 --> 00:07:51.345
SHARON: You can have him back, Terry.
I don't want him anymore.

146
00:07:51.429 --> 00:07:53.055
What was so much better about
being with Sharon, Rudy?

147
00:07:53.222 --> 00:07:54.348
Dad, don't answer that.

148
00:07:54.515 --> 00:07:56.476
We went to
the Metropolitan Museum of Art.

149
00:07:56.684 --> 00:07:57.727
TERRY: What did you like at the museum?

150
00:07:57.852 --> 00:07:59.145
RUDY: What did I like?
I'll tell you what I like.

151
00:07:59.312 --> 00:08:03.149
I like the ancient Roman statues.
I like the medieval armor.

152
00:08:03.316 --> 00:08:05.026
I like the Etruscan jewelry.

153
00:08:05.193 --> 00:08:07.737
-Museums are full of dust and death.
-RUDY: I like going to the café...

154
00:08:07.862 --> 00:08:10.031
having an expresso, a nice panini,
that's what I like.

155
00:08:10.072 --> 00:08:12.200
You had a panini in a coffin, Rudy.

156
00:08:12.366 --> 00:08:15.244
-A dusty, boring coffin. Yuck.
-RUDY: Then why'd you ask me?

157
00:08:15.411 --> 00:08:16.871
What are you, a crazy person?
It's like having

158
00:08:16.996 --> 00:08:18.206
a conversation
with an insane asylum person.

159
00:08:18.414 --> 00:08:19.749
What else, Captain Jack?
What else was so great?

160
00:08:19.916 --> 00:08:21.501
Captain Jack, you're calling me. Okay.

161
00:08:21.542 --> 00:08:22.710
Yes, you're Captain Jack,
the flying jackass.

162
00:08:22.793 --> 00:08:23.794
Yeah, and you know what you are?

163
00:08:23.878 --> 00:08:25.338
You're like a gas leak.
We don't smell you,

164
00:08:25.379 --> 00:08:26.964
-we don't see you, but you're...
-I am not a gas leak!

165
00:08:27.048 --> 00:08:28.382
-...killing us all silently.
-You take that back...

166
00:08:28.466 --> 00:08:29.467
and tell me what else you did
with Sharon!

167
00:08:29.634 --> 00:08:31.010
You creature from the Black Lagoon.

168
00:08:31.177 --> 00:08:32.553
No! This conversation is over.

169
00:08:32.678 --> 00:08:33.679
SHARON: I'm leaving. Good luck.

170
00:08:33.721 --> 00:08:35.556
TERRY: Oh, my God. Here it goes.
Watch out, Joy.

171
00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:36.682
-He's gonna snap!
-(door closes)

172
00:08:36.724 --> 00:08:38.893
Oh, please. You want me to snap.
That's your whole routine. You...

173
00:08:39.018 --> 00:08:40.019
TERRY: Guard the china!

174
00:08:40.186 --> 00:08:42.188
-Hey, Terry, you like this?
-JOY: Dad, no!

175
00:08:42.355 --> 00:08:43.898
-How's this for snapping?
-(gasps)

176
00:08:44.398 --> 00:08:45.691
-No! No.
-How's this?

177
00:08:47.193 --> 00:08:48.319
This is snapping!

178
00:08:48.486 --> 00:08:50.821
JOY: Dad! Stop!
TERRY: He's disturbed, Joy!

179
00:08:50.988 --> 00:08:52.240
He's a disturbed man!

180
00:08:52.406 --> 00:08:54.242
-I'm disturbed?
-He's a damaged man!

181
00:08:54.408 --> 00:08:56.077
You're right, I am disturbed.

182
00:08:56.244 --> 00:08:57.662
You're the great disturber!

183
00:08:58.579 --> 00:08:59.580
I'm sorry, honey.

184
00:08:59.747 --> 00:09:00.873
I don't like this.

185
00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:02.583
You're not supposed to see
this kind of thing.

186
00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:05.002
I'm very, very sorry.
I apologize sincerely.

187
00:09:05.419 --> 00:09:08.172
RIDGE (on TV): It's not gonna happen, okay?
We have other...

188
00:09:08.839 --> 00:09:09.840
I'm gonna clean all this up.

189
00:09:10.007 --> 00:09:11.717
Dad, no. Don't clean it up.

190
00:09:11.884 --> 00:09:13.886
Dad, stop. Just don't, okay?

191
00:09:14.929 --> 00:09:17.890
Stop. I'll do it.
I just want to get you out of this room.

192
00:09:19.892 --> 00:09:20.935
Thank you.

193
00:09:21.102 --> 00:09:22.728
Hi, guys.
I'm sorry about all the yelling.

194
00:09:22.895 --> 00:09:24.939
Mimi's gonna take you
to the birthday party, okay?

195
00:09:25.106 --> 00:09:26.566
Hi, my sweethearts.

196
00:09:26.732 --> 00:09:28.734
-You broke things again.
-He did break stuff.

197
00:09:28.901 --> 00:09:30.570
I did break some things,
but Grandma was wrong.

198
00:09:30.736 --> 00:09:32.947
So I was a little wrong,
but she was really wrong.

199
00:09:33.114 --> 00:09:35.116
But Grandpa's gonna come
stay with us for a little while.

200
00:09:35.283 --> 00:09:36.742
ALL: Yay!

201
00:09:36.909 --> 00:09:39.620
A sleepover with Grandpa! Yay!

202
00:09:39.787 --> 00:09:43.291
Sharon never separated the wash.
The whites were always grey.

203
00:09:43.457 --> 00:09:44.625
But you have that magic touch, sweetheart,

204
00:09:44.709 --> 00:09:45.751
so could I give this to you, please?

205
00:09:45.793 --> 00:09:46.794
Yeah, I'll take care of it, yeah.

206
00:09:46.919 --> 00:09:48.462
-Just get your bag.
-What about my ledgers

207
00:09:48.588 --> 00:09:49.630
and all that stuff? My accounting books?

208
00:09:49.755 --> 00:09:50.798
I got them.
I'll get them to you later today.

209
00:09:50.965 --> 00:09:52.425
-I love you, Grandpa.
-RUDY: Love you.

210
00:09:52.592 --> 00:09:54.885
JOY: I did your taxes, I did your W-2s.
RUDY: Okay. Very important.

211
00:09:55.886 --> 00:09:58.306
(Tony singing in Spanish)

212
00:10:09.984 --> 00:10:11.652
-RUDY: You suck!
-(music stops)

213
00:10:11.777 --> 00:10:12.820
What is he doing here?

214
00:10:12.987 --> 00:10:14.071
Sharon brought him back...

215
00:10:14.238 --> 00:10:18.242
so he's gonna stay with us until he finds
a new love or a new place to live.

216
00:10:18.409 --> 00:10:19.660
You know how this goes.

217
00:10:20.328 --> 00:10:22.163
(both speaking Spanish)

218
00:10:30.171 --> 00:10:31.172
Dad, up.

219
00:10:31.297 --> 00:10:32.673
(Tony continues in Spanish)

220
00:10:33.799 --> 00:10:35.843
This is not the proper way to be divorced,
the two of you.

221
00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:37.511
You're gonna tell me how to be divorced?

222
00:10:37.678 --> 00:10:38.846
I'm a provider, Tom Jones.

223
00:10:38.971 --> 00:10:40.097
-I have my own business.
-(laughs)

224
00:10:40.264 --> 00:10:41.766
I help Joy with the mortgage.
What do you do?

225
00:10:41.932 --> 00:10:44.018
You sing all night
at Angela Starpoli's club.

226
00:10:44.185 --> 00:10:46.354
You get repeatedly fired
from Campbell's Soup.

227
00:10:46.520 --> 00:10:48.439
Okay, well, I'm gonna divide the basement.

228
00:10:48.606 --> 00:10:50.358
I'm divorced.
I can do whatever I want, Rudy.

229
00:10:50.524 --> 00:10:51.859
RUDY: This is not
the proper way to be divorced.

230
00:10:52.026 --> 00:10:53.694
JOY: And I'm about to be late for work.

231
00:10:53.861 --> 00:10:56.364
So please try not to fight
in front of the children, okay?

232
00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:57.657
Especially not physically.

233
00:10:57.823 --> 00:11:00.284
TONY: Rudy, you see this?
This microphone here?

234
00:11:00.868 --> 00:11:03.537
You touch it, and I kill you.

235
00:11:05.873 --> 00:11:06.874
Okay. I'm leaving.

236
00:11:07.041 --> 00:11:09.168
Please try not to kill each other
while I'm gone.

237
00:11:09.335 --> 00:11:11.379
RODERICK: You've gone mad.
This is all your fault!

238
00:11:11.545 --> 00:11:13.297
Clarinda. Clarinda! Don't.

239
00:11:13.464 --> 00:11:16.217
Clarinda, something terrible happened!
Stay away from him!

240
00:11:20.054 --> 00:11:22.723
Oh, my God.
I thought I fixed this thing.

241
00:11:22.890 --> 00:11:24.809
PEGGY: Nice job, Joy. Nice job.

242
00:11:24.975 --> 00:11:27.895
Peggy? What are you doing here?

243
00:11:28.813 --> 00:11:31.399
What's the matter with you?
Sending Grandma Mimi with her arthritis...

244
00:11:31.565 --> 00:11:33.234
to take them to their friend's birthday?

245
00:11:33.401 --> 00:11:34.568
Oh, I'm fine.

246
00:11:34.735 --> 00:11:38.030
PEGGY: They have a much better time
with me anyway, with Aunt Peggy.

247
00:11:38.072 --> 00:11:40.032
-MIMI: Uh-uh.
-But I wasn't stupid enough

248
00:11:40.074 --> 00:11:42.076
to get into a bad marriage
and have a couple of kids.

249
00:11:42.243 --> 00:11:43.411
MIMI: Don't bother your sister, Peggy.

250
00:11:43.577 --> 00:11:46.080
I'm gonna talk to Dad about business.
All right?

251
00:11:46.247 --> 00:11:47.832
You gonna come bring the books
by the garage later?

252
00:11:47.998 --> 00:11:49.500
Yeah, I'm gonna bring them later.
He's in the basement.

253
00:11:49.667 --> 00:11:50.668
I'm joking with you.

254
00:11:50.835 --> 00:11:51.919
(sighs) Yeah. I know.

255
00:11:52.086 --> 00:11:54.255
PEGGY: Kids, we're gonna do
something fun later, okay?

256
00:11:54.422 --> 00:11:56.090
MIMI: We're doing something fun now.

257
00:12:02.763 --> 00:12:05.182
JOY: Oh, we found your luggage
but it's in Cleveland.

258
00:12:05.349 --> 00:12:06.934
So now we just need to get it back
to New York City.

259
00:12:07.101 --> 00:12:08.269
WOMAN: I'm filing a complaint.

260
00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:11.272
My husband needs his medication.

261
00:12:11.605 --> 00:12:13.274
What's your name? Joy?

262
00:12:13.441 --> 00:12:15.192
You don't seem joyous to me today.

263
00:12:15.359 --> 00:12:17.111
Perhaps I am not so joyous today.

264
00:12:17.236 --> 00:12:19.405
-Joy, I think you're getting demoted.
-Hi, how you doing?

265
00:12:19.447 --> 00:12:21.115
Listen, I need you to speak
to the supervisor.

266
00:12:21.282 --> 00:12:23.117
We're gonna be having some changes,

267
00:12:23.242 --> 00:12:24.910
and you're gonna be
going to the night hours.

268
00:12:24.952 --> 00:12:26.787
Night hours? Tom, I can't work night hours.

269
00:12:26.912 --> 00:12:28.289
-And we're having cutbacks.
-I've got two kids.

270
00:12:28.414 --> 00:12:29.582
SUSAN: Joy, I'm sorry. Good luck.

271
00:12:29.623 --> 00:12:30.708
Bye, Susan.

272
00:12:31.041 --> 00:12:33.294
WOMAN:
<i>♪ I want to be happy ♪</i>

273
00:12:33.377 --> 00:12:35.296
<i>♪ But I won't be happy ♪</i>

274
00:12:35.421 --> 00:12:36.464
(men laughing)

275
00:12:36.547 --> 00:12:38.257
<i>♪ Till I make you happy, too ♪</i>

276
00:12:38.299 --> 00:12:39.800
-(gunfire)
-(indistinct chatter)

277
00:12:40.426 --> 00:12:44.472
<i>♪ Life's really worth living</i>
<i>When we are mirth-giving ♪</i>

278
00:12:45.139 --> 00:12:48.976
<i>♪ Why can't I give some to you? ♪</i>

279
00:12:49.769 --> 00:12:51.145
<i>♪ When skies are gray... ♪</i>

280
00:12:51.312 --> 00:12:53.647
RUDY: I'm not paying for metal
that I haven't gotten.

281
00:12:53.773 --> 00:12:55.733
On top of me send...
You know, he wants to get paid.

282
00:12:55.816 --> 00:12:57.943
He doesn't send an invoice,
and he hasn't even sent the metal.

283
00:12:59.153 --> 00:13:02.156
But why doesn't he just send the invoice?
Send the invoice, I'll pay him.

284
00:13:02.907 --> 00:13:04.658
Yep. That's it. Send the invoice.

285
00:13:06.577 --> 00:13:09.163
Hi. Dad, I want to thank you again
for helping with the mortgage.

286
00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:10.748
Yeah.

287
00:13:10.873 --> 00:13:12.333
I settled the accounts,

288
00:13:12.416 --> 00:13:14.126
-balanced the books.
-Thank you.

289
00:13:14.293 --> 00:13:15.920
I'm sorry business is so bad, Dad.

290
00:13:16.086 --> 00:13:18.589
I don't think that
that crazy gun range is helping.

291
00:13:19.173 --> 00:13:20.508
How is that still legal?

292
00:13:20.674 --> 00:13:22.468
-What can I do?
-After all these years?

293
00:13:22.635 --> 00:13:24.303
They keep to themselves.

294
00:13:24.470 --> 00:13:26.347
It's their property.
The police leave them alone.

295
00:13:26.514 --> 00:13:28.182
Why? You think it's costing us business?

296
00:13:28.349 --> 00:13:29.683
-I don't think it's helping.
-(door opens)

297
00:13:30.684 --> 00:13:33.103
Well, if you wanna help, why don't you
come here and manage this place?

298
00:13:33.270 --> 00:13:35.940
You know, I'd like to go the next level.
Put on a nice suit.

299
00:13:36.106 --> 00:13:38.025
You know, go out there
and get some accounts.

300
00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:39.610
Shh.

301
00:13:39.693 --> 00:13:43.823
Yeah, this is 9873.
Just checking my mailbox.

302
00:13:44.198 --> 00:13:45.199
What is that?

303
00:13:45.366 --> 00:13:46.534
Yeah, I have a pen. What is it?

304
00:13:46.784 --> 00:13:49.203
13-14. That's it?

305
00:13:49.453 --> 00:13:50.621
Thank you.

306
00:13:50.788 --> 00:13:52.164
What was that?

307
00:13:52.331 --> 00:13:54.375
It's a 900 number.

308
00:13:54.625 --> 00:13:55.876
What's a 900 number?

309
00:13:56.544 --> 00:14:00.172
It's, you know, a dating service
for widows and widowers.

310
00:14:00.339 --> 00:14:01.465
JOY: Dating service?

311
00:14:01.632 --> 00:14:02.883
You're not a widow or a widower.

312
00:14:03.050 --> 00:14:04.301
What's the difference? I'm single.

313
00:14:04.468 --> 00:14:07.346
I meet nice ladies.
Maybe we fall in love.

314
00:14:07.513 --> 00:14:09.890
I have to fall in love or I'm not interested.
You know me.

315
00:14:10.057 --> 00:14:11.976
-I know, Dad.
-Shh.

316
00:14:12.059 --> 00:14:14.937
(whispering) Sharon was no good for him.
It's nice for him to meet somebody new.

317
00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:17.064
-I got him some new clothes, you know?
-Okay. Okay.

318
00:14:17.231 --> 00:14:18.732
-RUDY: Hello? Is this 7633?
-It's good.

319
00:14:18.899 --> 00:14:19.900
Okay. I love you. See you later.

320
00:14:20.025 --> 00:14:21.819
-WOMAN (on phone): Yes?
-Bye.

321
00:14:21.986 --> 00:14:23.737
Hi. This is 9833.

322
00:14:23.821 --> 00:14:26.323
Oh! Hi! Hi, how are you?

323
00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:27.908
-What a nice voice you have.
-(door closes)

324
00:14:27.992 --> 00:14:29.243
Oh, thank you.

325
00:14:29.577 --> 00:14:31.662
RUDY: Oh, an accent.
WOMAN: Yes.

326
00:14:31.829 --> 00:14:33.080
I am from Italy.

327
00:14:33.247 --> 00:14:35.416
-RUDY: Oh! Continental.
-Mmm-hmm.

328
00:14:35.541 --> 00:14:36.584
What is your name?

329
00:14:36.709 --> 00:14:37.751
My name is Rudy,

330
00:14:37.835 --> 00:14:39.420
-what's yours?
-Trudy.

331
00:14:40.004 --> 00:14:41.755
-Are you kidding me?
-(laughing) No.

332
00:14:41.922 --> 00:14:42.923
Your name is Trudy?

333
00:14:43.048 --> 00:14:44.049
Yes!

334
00:14:44.216 --> 00:14:45.551
Rudy and Trudy. I love it.

335
00:14:45.926 --> 00:14:48.387
Let's figure out when we're gonna meet.

336
00:14:48.554 --> 00:14:50.598
That's a good idea. Let's have dinner.

337
00:14:51.015 --> 00:14:52.266
-I could come pick you up.
-Yeah.

338
00:14:52.433 --> 00:14:53.767
I have a green Mercedes.

339
00:14:53.934 --> 00:14:55.936
Okay, 6:30? I'll be ready.

340
00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:57.021
Ciao.

341
00:14:57.104 --> 00:14:58.230
(hangs up)

342
00:14:58.272 --> 00:14:59.690
Good luck with your date, Dad.

343
00:14:59.857 --> 00:15:01.108
RUDY: Thank you. I'm excited.

344
00:15:01.275 --> 00:15:02.776
What do you think you're gonna wear?

345
00:15:04.278 --> 00:15:06.405
Polo by Ralph Lauren.

346
00:15:06.572 --> 00:15:07.573
Did you have to use the whole

347
00:15:07.615 --> 00:15:09.158
-bottle of cologne? Huh?
-JOY: Tony!

348
00:15:09.241 --> 00:15:11.076
You smell like my grandmother.
He smells like my grandmother.

349
00:15:11.243 --> 00:15:12.912
Hey, please. Don't make me tense.

350
00:15:13.078 --> 00:15:15.915
Don't stress me out.
I gotta stay nice and loose.

351
00:15:15.956 --> 00:15:18.292
TONY: Now you're tense?
RUDY: I'm tense. You're making me tense.

352
00:15:18.417 --> 00:15:19.460
Guys, stop. Please.

353
00:15:19.543 --> 00:15:20.753
-TONY: I'm making you tense?
-(car horn honking)

354
00:15:20.794 --> 00:15:21.962
My carriage awaits.

355
00:15:22.129 --> 00:15:23.422
Have a great date.

356
00:15:23.589 --> 00:15:24.590
Wish me luck.

357
00:15:24.757 --> 00:15:25.799
You don't need it.

358
00:15:25.883 --> 00:15:27.009
(door closes)

359
00:15:27.134 --> 00:15:28.302
Joy, water!

360
00:15:28.469 --> 00:15:29.470
TONY: Where are my cufflinks?

361
00:15:29.637 --> 00:15:31.430
CRISTY: Mommy, come read to me!

362
00:15:31.472 --> 00:15:32.556
Five minutes, Cristy.

363
00:15:32.765 --> 00:15:33.974
Mother, again?

364
00:15:34.808 --> 00:15:37.478
(groans) Yeah, you just sit right there.
Are you comfortable?

365
00:15:37.895 --> 00:15:43.150
How many times do I have to tell you
not to clean your brushes out in the sink!

366
00:15:43.317 --> 00:15:45.778
Danica thinks it's unladylike
to toss things in the toilet.

367
00:15:45.945 --> 00:15:47.112
And I happen to agree.

368
00:15:47.279 --> 00:15:49.490
Yeah? Well, why don't you have
Danica do your plumbing then?

369
00:15:49.657 --> 00:15:53.285
Danica can direct her power
anywhere Danica chooses.

370
00:15:53.452 --> 00:15:55.829
-That is the power of Danica.
-(floorboards creaking)

371
00:15:55.996 --> 00:15:57.331
(grunts)

372
00:15:58.499 --> 00:15:59.792
JOY: Oh, my God.

373
00:15:59.959 --> 00:16:02.169
If this problem gets any worse...

374
00:16:03.253 --> 00:16:05.464
we're gonna have to move you
into a different room.

375
00:16:05.631 --> 00:16:07.132
That means no TV.

376
00:16:07.758 --> 00:16:09.510
That could be very scary for you.

377
00:16:10.469 --> 00:16:13.347
Don't let that happen, Joy.
This is my comfort nest.

378
00:16:13.430 --> 00:16:16.350
(sighs) We're gonna need to get
a plumber in here.

379
00:16:16.517 --> 00:16:17.601
TERRY: What?

380
00:16:18.352 --> 00:16:21.021
(stammers) There's gonna...
A man in my room?

381
00:16:21.188 --> 00:16:23.440
JOY: Well, I don't know
any female plumbers other than me.

382
00:16:23.607 --> 00:16:25.025
Well, can't you fix it, Joy?

383
00:16:25.192 --> 00:16:27.611
This has surpassed my capabilities.

384
00:16:27.778 --> 00:16:28.862
Thanks, Joy.

385
00:16:29.822 --> 00:16:32.700
"The cicada is a large flying insect
two to three inches long.

386
00:16:32.866 --> 00:16:36.453
"It makes a sound of up to 120 decibels,
louder than some telephones.

387
00:16:37.287 --> 00:16:40.874
"It lives half of its life above ground
evading predators."

388
00:16:41.041 --> 00:16:42.668
This is the book you wanted me
to read to you, Cristy?

389
00:16:42.835 --> 00:16:44.211
How did this book even get in the house?

390
00:16:44.795 --> 00:16:46.296
Aunt Peggy got it for me.

391
00:16:46.463 --> 00:16:50.884
She said the reason I like cicadas
is because they fill the air with sound...

392
00:16:51.051 --> 00:16:53.137
which makes the house less lonelier for me.

393
00:16:53.846 --> 00:16:57.182
Aunt Peggy tells you how you feel
about the house being lonely?

394
00:16:57.349 --> 00:16:58.809
Aunt Peggy tells me a lot of things.

395
00:16:58.976 --> 00:17:00.352
Keep reading, please.

396
00:17:01.895 --> 00:17:04.314
I don't want you
listening to Aunt Peggy too much.

397
00:17:04.481 --> 00:17:05.858
Okay. Why?

398
00:17:07.067 --> 00:17:09.528
"The cicada,
a symbol of rebirth in many countries...

399
00:17:09.695 --> 00:17:13.365
"digs into the ground and stays buried
for up to 17 years."

400
00:17:14.033 --> 00:17:17.077
That's such a random number.
Why 17 years?

401
00:17:17.870 --> 00:17:18.996
It doesn't even say why.

402
00:17:19.163 --> 00:17:22.166
I understand the four seasons in a year...

403
00:17:22.332 --> 00:17:24.752
but why would something
stay hidden for 17 years?

404
00:17:24.918 --> 00:17:27.588
That's just unsettling.
I'm not reading this.

405
00:17:27.755 --> 00:17:29.840
You're sleepy anyway.
We gotta go to bed.

406
00:17:31.091 --> 00:17:32.885
I wanna sleep with Nana.

407
00:17:33.052 --> 00:17:34.511
No, you should sleep upstairs
in your room.

408
00:17:34.678 --> 00:17:36.263
I want Nana.

409
00:17:36.722 --> 00:17:38.015
(Joy sighs)

410
00:17:38.098 --> 00:17:39.933
All right. Well, watch out.
There's a hole here.

411
00:17:46.273 --> 00:17:48.108
Just going to lay down for a second.

412
00:17:50.110 --> 00:17:52.362
I feel like I'm in a prison.

413
00:17:52.529 --> 00:17:55.115
No, Bartholomew's the ex-con
in the story.

414
00:17:55.282 --> 00:17:57.242
And Clarinda doesn't even know about it.

415
00:17:57.409 --> 00:17:59.078
But Danica's onto him.

416
00:18:00.245 --> 00:18:02.873
They all blame Clarinda
but Danica's gonna get to the bottom of it.

417
00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:04.124
No. No.

418
00:18:04.291 --> 00:18:06.710
-Yes. It was you Clarinda.
-(Joy breathing heavily)

419
00:18:06.877 --> 00:18:08.128
I will get to the bottom of this.

420
00:18:08.295 --> 00:18:09.922
You've made terrible mistakes.

421
00:18:10.089 --> 00:18:11.465
It was Clarinda!

422
00:18:12.091 --> 00:18:13.926
(hymn playing)

423
00:18:14.259 --> 00:18:15.302
Oh.

424
00:18:15.469 --> 00:18:16.470
Look who's here.

425
00:18:16.637 --> 00:18:17.638
Look who's here.

426
00:18:18.097 --> 00:18:19.139
Look who's here.

427
00:18:20.307 --> 00:18:21.308
(continues breathing heavily)

428
00:18:26.313 --> 00:18:27.314
(tires screeching)

429
00:18:40.327 --> 00:18:43.413
YOUNG JOY: We are here today
to remember what was lost...

430
00:18:43.580 --> 00:18:45.833
seventeen years ago.

431
00:18:45.999 --> 00:18:48.085
Do you remember?

432
00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:51.672
RUDY: Peggy comes with me.

433
00:18:51.839 --> 00:18:53.841
Joy spends half the time with us.

434
00:18:54.591 --> 00:18:56.093
We'll take her paper forest.

435
00:18:56.260 --> 00:18:58.470
TERRY: That's Joy's special thing,
and it belongs in this house.

436
00:18:58.637 --> 00:18:59.680
RUDY: No, I...

437
00:19:11.024 --> 00:19:12.985
-(doorbell ringing)
-TERRY: Joy.

438
00:19:14.862 --> 00:19:16.029
Joy, wake up!

439
00:19:16.655 --> 00:19:18.490
Someone's been ringing the doorbell.

440
00:19:18.657 --> 00:19:20.200
(ringing continues)

441
00:19:29.459 --> 00:19:30.878
(knocking on door)

442
00:19:32.504 --> 00:19:33.714
Jackie!

443
00:19:34.173 --> 00:19:35.215
Oh, thank God! It's you.

444
00:19:35.382 --> 00:19:37.384
What happened? I'm worried about you.

445
00:19:37.509 --> 00:19:38.802
-I don't see you any more.
-(exhales)

446
00:19:38.969 --> 00:19:40.679
You don't come to the PTA.

447
00:19:41.138 --> 00:19:43.056
You know how my mom's
always clogging the sink

448
00:19:43.182 --> 00:19:45.058
with her hair from the brushes?

449
00:19:45.225 --> 00:19:46.518
JACKIE: With the pipes in her room?

450
00:19:46.685 --> 00:19:47.978
Yeah. She did it again.

451
00:19:48.103 --> 00:19:49.396
Again?

452
00:19:49.563 --> 00:19:51.815
Yes, and I had to
bash open a hole in the floor.

453
00:19:51.982 --> 00:19:55.819
There's a huge hole in the floor
of my mother's room and I'm broke.

454
00:19:57.362 --> 00:20:01.074
My father works hard.
He's had some bad breaks.

455
00:20:03.577 --> 00:20:06.914
I hope he gets another girlfriend,
and he'll move out of the basement.

456
00:20:07.372 --> 00:20:08.749
He's in the basement with Tony?

457
00:20:08.916 --> 00:20:11.585
Yes. And they hate each other.

458
00:20:12.252 --> 00:20:13.587
Yes.

459
00:20:14.379 --> 00:20:16.924
It's a disaster.
They won't stop fighting.

460
00:20:18.592 --> 00:20:19.593
I don't know.

461
00:20:20.594 --> 00:20:23.597
But how are you?
How's the family? How is everybody?

462
00:20:23.764 --> 00:20:24.765
Everybody's okay.

463
00:20:24.932 --> 00:20:26.099
How's work?

464
00:20:26.767 --> 00:20:29.061
My job, I could take it or leave it.

465
00:20:29.895 --> 00:20:32.105
What happened to us, Jackie?

466
00:20:32.272 --> 00:20:34.775
All the things
that we used to dream about.

467
00:20:34.942 --> 00:20:37.903
I feel like they just keep getting
farther and farther away.

468
00:20:38.111 --> 00:20:40.948
JACKIE: Remember the night of the party
where everything started?

469
00:20:41.365 --> 00:20:42.908
-The band was playing.
-(Latin music playing)

470
00:20:43.408 --> 00:20:45.035
<i>Everything was so exciting.</i>

471
00:20:45.244 --> 00:20:46.578
(indistinct conversations)

472
00:20:46.912 --> 00:20:48.455
Joy, you came!

473
00:20:48.622 --> 00:20:51.208
I'm so glad you came!
This is my boyfriend, Andre.

474
00:20:51.375 --> 00:20:52.584
-Hi, Andre.
-Nice to meet you.

475
00:20:52.751 --> 00:20:54.461
Andre, this is my childhood friend, Joy.

476
00:20:54.962 --> 00:20:56.088
Come inside!

477
00:20:56.380 --> 00:20:58.590
-Wow.
-Check my music class, accountant girl.

478
00:20:58.757 --> 00:20:59.800
This is a class?

479
00:20:59.925 --> 00:21:00.968
Yes!

480
00:21:01.134 --> 00:21:02.219
♪ Don't turn on the lights ♪

481
00:21:02.302 --> 00:21:03.887
♪ 'Cause I don't wanna see ♪

482
00:21:04.054 --> 00:21:06.306
♪ Mama told me not to come ♪

483
00:21:06.431 --> 00:21:08.600
JOY: They're so good!
JACKIE: They are! The teacher's band.

484
00:21:08.642 --> 00:21:09.977
