Give her a children's cough medicine.

730
00:32:00.460 --> 00:32:01.753
-That's what does it.
-TONY: Is that safe?

731
00:32:01.920 --> 00:32:03.129
MIMI: No. It's not safe.

732
00:32:03.296 --> 00:32:04.380
It's expired.

733
00:32:05.298 --> 00:32:07.467
Go on, there. Knock it back, honey.

734
00:32:07.592 --> 00:32:10.053
-MIMI: No.
-Okay, one more. Knock it down. Come on.

735
00:32:10.219 --> 00:32:11.804
-Rudy!
-Do it, Tony.

736
00:32:11.971 --> 00:32:13.556
-I don't know.
-Just do it. One more.

737
00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:14.641
Okay, one more.

738
00:32:14.766 --> 00:32:17.143
Enough with this! That's it.
I'm gonna make her a hot toddy.

739
00:32:17.310 --> 00:32:18.436
That's what she needs.

740
00:32:18.603 --> 00:32:19.646
TONY: You're gonna intoxicate her.

741
00:32:19.812 --> 00:32:22.482
RUDY: It's all natural, it's all herbal.
Nothing strong.

742
00:32:22.649 --> 00:32:28.947
I was kidnapped by another monk,
who was from Switzerland.

743
00:32:30.615 --> 00:32:37.413
And it turned out that this monk
was a duke of a royal family.

744
00:32:38.581 --> 00:32:41.834
I shouldn't say "was," because he still is.

745
00:32:42.251 --> 00:32:43.753
Leave me alone.

746
00:32:44.754 --> 00:32:46.464
I don't think we should let her
sleep on the stairs.

747
00:32:47.173 --> 00:32:49.634
TONY: Let's put her here
on the couch, okay?

748
00:32:53.930 --> 00:32:55.765
(hymn playing)

749
00:32:59.102 --> 00:33:00.186
(door closes)

750
00:33:02.689 --> 00:33:04.774
YOUNG JOY: Seventeen years.

751
00:33:04.941 --> 00:33:07.527
Think about it. We've been hiding...

752
00:33:07.694 --> 00:33:10.446
for seventeen years.

753
00:33:11.656 --> 00:33:13.700
Seventeen years.

754
00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:17.662
We used to make things.
Seventeen years ago.

755
00:33:18.121 --> 00:33:20.498
Then, that all stopped.
What happened?

756
00:33:22.291 --> 00:33:25.378
When you're hiding, you're safe...

757
00:33:25.837 --> 00:33:28.548
because people can't see you.

758
00:33:28.881 --> 00:33:31.843
But, funny thing about hiding...

759
00:33:32.218 --> 00:33:34.637
you're even hidden from yourself.

760
00:33:48.026 --> 00:33:49.694
Baby, what's the matter?

761
00:33:49.736 --> 00:33:50.820
(sighs)

762
00:33:50.903 --> 00:33:52.905
Tony, you need to move out
of the basement.

763
00:33:53.072 --> 00:33:54.657
You need to get your own house.

764
00:33:54.824 --> 00:33:56.242
What? Why?

765
00:33:56.826 --> 00:33:59.370
Because I go out at night
and sing at Angela's club?

766
00:33:59.537 --> 00:34:00.663
-Is that it?
-No.

767
00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:03.082
Because we've been divorced
for two years.

768
00:34:03.249 --> 00:34:04.751
We need to move on.

769
00:34:04.917 --> 00:34:06.252
You need to move out.

770
00:34:07.086 --> 00:34:08.421
Rudy, you need to move out, too.

771
00:34:08.546 --> 00:34:09.756
RUDY: What?

772
00:34:09.922 --> 00:34:12.050
There's more room in the basement
for me now.

773
00:34:12.592 --> 00:34:13.676
JOY: And another thing, Rudy.

774
00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:16.429
Tomorrow, I would like to have a meeting
with you and Trudy at your office...

775
00:34:16.512 --> 00:34:20.016
to discuss her investing
in the manufacturing of my new idea.

776
00:34:20.099 --> 00:34:21.184
No.

777
00:34:21.350 --> 00:34:23.186
I'm still getting to know her
and falling in love.

778
00:34:23.352 --> 00:34:25.563
I can't do that. I won't do that.

779
00:34:26.064 --> 00:34:28.441
And what manufacturing idea?
What are you talking about?

780
00:34:29.901 --> 00:34:33.237
I have always been there for you,
no matter what.

781
00:34:33.613 --> 00:34:34.781
I didn't go away to school.

782
00:34:34.947 --> 00:34:37.617
I stayed to help you and Mom
through the divorce and do your accounting.

783
00:34:38.117 --> 00:34:40.453
I let you live here whenever you want...

784
00:34:40.787 --> 00:34:42.705
no matter what it is.

785
00:34:43.456 --> 00:34:47.919
I am respectfully asking
for the favor that you owe me.

786
00:34:49.253 --> 00:34:52.048
If you look into your heart,
you'll know that I'm right.

787
00:34:56.636 --> 00:35:01.808
Cristy, I need to use your crayons,
your colored pencils and your paper.

788
00:35:02.600 --> 00:35:04.102
Let's go to my room.

789
00:35:40.012 --> 00:35:41.180
JOY: You're not gonna believe this.

790
00:35:41.347 --> 00:35:43.474
So, you know that plumber
that you recommended?

791
00:35:43.641 --> 00:35:44.684
JACKIE: Yeah, Touissant.

792
00:35:44.851 --> 00:35:48.437
So I hire him, Terry freaks out,
completely disoriented.

793
00:35:48.604 --> 00:35:51.149
Hasn't had a man in her room
for eight years, since Rudy.

794
00:35:51.315 --> 00:35:52.984
Makes me hang a drop cloth.

795
00:35:53.151 --> 00:35:54.152
The way I look at it...

796
00:35:54.360 --> 00:35:57.613
is that this is an opportunity
for you to invest in a new business...

797
00:35:59.490 --> 00:36:01.284
...that'll mean more money for you.

798
00:36:02.869 --> 00:36:04.537
Tell Rico, Dad. Number five's gotta go off.

799
00:36:04.704 --> 00:36:07.540
Rico, number five, no, off.

800
00:36:07.707 --> 00:36:09.876
(mouthing) Go off! Thank you!

801
00:36:11.043 --> 00:36:13.296
It's a standard handle, 53 inches.

802
00:36:13.462 --> 00:36:15.506
The sleeve connects to the mop head.

803
00:36:15.673 --> 00:36:17.800
Now, this is where it gets complicated.

804
00:36:18.176 --> 00:36:21.220
There's a clip
that connects the sleeve to the...

805
00:36:21.804 --> 00:36:24.348
I don't even know what to call it.
The "cup. "

806
00:36:24.849 --> 00:36:26.392
Which is connected to the mop head.

807
00:36:26.726 --> 00:36:29.979
So, when you pull up on the sleeve,
the mop head stretches...

808
00:36:30.062 --> 00:36:32.732
so you can wring it
without ever touching it with your hands.

809
00:36:33.191 --> 00:36:36.235
The only thing we see
is this crayon drawings.

810
00:36:36.402 --> 00:36:37.820
We can't make heads or tails.

811
00:36:38.404 --> 00:36:39.822
We don't know what it is.

812
00:36:40.406 --> 00:36:43.576
So, the mop doesn't hang loose, like hair?
Like a string?

813
00:36:43.743 --> 00:36:45.870
It hangs, but not on loose,
open ends like hair.

814
00:36:46.037 --> 00:36:47.705
It's one continuous loop.

815
00:36:47.747 --> 00:36:48.873
-I don't get it.
-PEGGY: I don't get it.

816
00:36:48.915 --> 00:36:51.334
-I don't get it. What's he doing here?
-What's he doing here?

817
00:36:51.500 --> 00:36:54.503
He is the father of our children,
and my friend, and he looks out for me.

818
00:37:02.553 --> 00:37:04.513
We're doing an invention.

819
00:37:04.931 --> 00:37:06.098
Cheers.

820
00:37:06.599 --> 00:37:07.767
Right.

821
00:37:09.852 --> 00:37:11.604
Yes we are, Cristy.

822
00:37:12.438 --> 00:37:14.232
It's very serious.

823
00:37:14.857 --> 00:37:16.400
It's priority.

824
00:37:16.567 --> 00:37:17.610
JOY: Yes it is.

825
00:37:17.777 --> 00:37:18.778
CRISTY: And I'm helping.

826
00:37:18.945 --> 00:37:20.613
JOY: Yes you are.

827
00:37:30.623 --> 00:37:32.625
<i>Ça se fait comme ça</i> in Haiti.

828
00:37:32.792 --> 00:37:35.086
Touissant is teaching me
how to speak French.

829
00:37:35.711 --> 00:37:37.630
And the word for "industrious" is...

830
00:37:38.214 --> 00:37:39.590
(speaks French)

831
00:37:39.715 --> 00:37:42.260
Yes. At first I thought
maybe something scary would happen...

832
00:37:42.426 --> 00:37:46.305
like what happened with Danica
while she was kidnapped by a man...

833
00:37:46.472 --> 00:37:49.100
who turned out to be in hiding
from the royal family in Switzerland...

834
00:37:49.267 --> 00:37:51.477
and then she moved to Switzerland.

835
00:37:51.644 --> 00:37:53.813
Of course, she befriended that man
and more.

836
00:37:54.313 --> 00:37:56.232
Don't ever try and limit me, Joy.

837
00:37:56.399 --> 00:37:58.401
And let me know if you want some
of this Chakalaka.

838
00:37:58.567 --> 00:37:59.568
Chaka. Say "chaka."

839
00:37:59.735 --> 00:38:01.404
-Chaka.
-It's very good.

840
00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:05.491
(both saying goodbye in French)

841
00:38:06.158 --> 00:38:08.077
(hammering)

842
00:38:09.495 --> 00:38:11.247
Hey, Rocky. Hey, Tom!

843
00:38:12.915 --> 00:38:14.250
Take her inside the office.

844
00:38:15.293 --> 00:38:17.670
-Hey, Tino.
-Hey, Joy.

845
00:38:17.837 --> 00:38:19.672
I wanted to show you something.

846
00:38:19.839 --> 00:38:21.299
So, will you help me figure this out?

847
00:38:21.465 --> 00:38:24.510
I know that it has to be welded.
This part is supposed to twist.

848
00:38:51.037 --> 00:38:54.874
JOY: <i>1... 2... 3...</i>

849
00:38:55.207 --> 00:38:58.127
BOTH: 4, 5, 6...

850
00:38:58.711 --> 00:38:59.712
RUDY: What are you doing?

851
00:39:00.046 --> 00:39:01.464
(both continue counting)

852
00:39:05.551 --> 00:39:08.804
JOY: 38, 39, 40.

853
00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:12.183
All right. All right, Dad,
come over here and grab this.

854
00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:13.976
Grab it right in the middle.

855
00:39:18.564 --> 00:39:19.565
Okay. There.

856
00:39:19.732 --> 00:39:22.360
And go up, Jackie go down. You see it?

857
00:39:22.401 --> 00:39:23.486
Not yet.

858
00:39:23.569 --> 00:39:25.571
All right. Here.

859
00:39:26.530 --> 00:39:27.865
-How about now?
-No.

860
00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:29.909
JOY: Well, you're going to.

861
00:39:30.076 --> 00:39:32.244
I don't see it yet, I mean...

862
00:39:36.582 --> 00:39:38.751
-You ready?
-Yeah.

863
00:39:40.336 --> 00:39:42.088
ALL: Oh!

864
00:39:45.758 --> 00:39:48.344
300 feet of continuous cotton loops.

865
00:39:48.761 --> 00:39:50.388
That's what I drew.

866
00:39:51.097 --> 00:39:55.518
This is why I would like to ask you
for your investment, Trudy.

867
00:39:56.769 --> 00:40:00.606
Morris worked 50 years
to earn his fortune, Joy.

868
00:40:01.565 --> 00:40:06.028
Before he passed on to the next world,
he made me promise on his deathbed...

869
00:40:06.195 --> 00:40:10.199
that I would never be neglectful
with one dollar of the money...

870
00:40:10.366 --> 00:40:12.451
that he so carefully earned.

871
00:40:13.119 --> 00:40:18.457
Therefore you have to answer Morris's
four questions of financial worthiness.

872
00:40:18.624 --> 00:40:19.750
Are you ready?

873
00:40:20.876 --> 00:40:22.253
I think so. Yes.

874
00:40:23.796 --> 00:40:25.464
Question number one:

875
00:40:26.215 --> 00:40:28.384
Where did you go to high school?

876
00:40:28.551 --> 00:40:30.094
Plainfield Public High.

877
00:40:30.219 --> 00:40:34.473
Question number two:
Who were you in high school?

878
00:40:35.224 --> 00:40:37.059
-I was valedictorian.
-Ah.

879
00:40:37.768 --> 00:40:40.187
The smartest student in the school.

880
00:40:40.354 --> 00:40:41.647
That's good, right?

881
00:40:42.565 --> 00:40:43.732
Perhaps.

882
00:40:44.316 --> 00:40:50.030
Joy might be a brilliant,
unrealized creator of commerce.

883
00:40:50.489 --> 00:40:51.490
But on the other hand...

884
00:40:51.657 --> 00:40:55.494
it's equally possible that she is
a fatally flawed underachiever...

885
00:40:55.661 --> 00:41:00.749
doomed to a lifetime of failure,
disappointment, unfulfilled expectations.

886
00:41:01.876 --> 00:41:03.461
You must admit, Joy...

887
00:41:03.627 --> 00:41:06.672
that your life, to date,
makes a stronger case for...

888
00:41:07.631 --> 00:41:09.008
...disappointment.

889
00:41:11.218 --> 00:41:12.595
I don't care about any of this.

890
00:41:12.761 --> 00:41:15.556
It's not only risky,
but it's fiscally irresponsible...

891
00:41:15.723 --> 00:41:18.058
and doesn't make any sense, whatsoever.

892
00:41:18.225 --> 00:41:19.560
Joy's never run a business in her life.

893
00:41:19.727 --> 00:41:22.062
I've been running my father's garage
for the last 10 years.

894
00:41:22.771 --> 00:41:24.356
Our father.

895
00:41:25.566 --> 00:41:27.902
I have ventures that I'm planning
to launch here...

896
00:41:28.068 --> 00:41:30.029
at this existing business.

897
00:41:30.196 --> 00:41:32.490
You never mentioned any of this...

898
00:41:32.656 --> 00:41:34.825
until I came to Trudy
to ask for an investment.

899
00:41:35.701 --> 00:41:37.995
What's Morris's third question?

900
00:41:38.162 --> 00:41:39.538
TRUDY: Are you prepared...

901
00:41:39.705 --> 00:41:43.083
within six months of commencing
this venture...

902
00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:45.252
to show adequate returns?

903
00:41:46.086 --> 00:41:47.671
I accept your terms.

904
00:41:47.838 --> 00:41:49.215
Don't do it, Joy.

905
00:41:49.381 --> 00:41:51.217
What's the fourth question?

906
00:41:51.425 --> 00:41:55.804
You are in a room,
and there is a gun on the table.

907
00:41:55.971 --> 00:42:00.559
And the only other person in the room
is an adversary in commerce.

908
00:42:00.726 --> 00:42:02.978
Only one of you can prevail.

909
00:42:03.145 --> 00:42:08.901
Yet, you have protected your business
and Morris's money.

910
00:42:10.819 --> 00:42:13.030
Do you pick up the gun, Joy?

911
00:42:14.657 --> 00:42:16.784
That's a very strange question.

912
00:42:16.951 --> 00:42:20.829
There is nothing strange
about this question at all.

913
00:42:20.996 --> 00:42:22.915
This is money.

914
00:42:24.124 --> 00:42:27.920
Do you pick up the gun?

915
00:42:28.879 --> 00:42:30.339
I pick up the gun.

916
00:42:30.506 --> 00:42:31.632
Good.

917
00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:35.010
I'm going to remember that you said that...

918
00:42:36.011 --> 00:42:38.472
when I speak to my lawyer.

919
00:42:39.515 --> 00:42:41.725
CRISTY: <i>What did Trudy's lawyer say?</i>

920
00:42:41.892 --> 00:42:43.852
He did a worldwide patent search.

921
00:42:44.019 --> 00:42:45.479
What's a patent?

922
00:42:46.355 --> 00:42:49.817
A patent is like a law
that you get to protect your idea.

923
00:42:50.234 --> 00:42:52.319
A lot of people patent their ideas...

924
00:42:52.486 --> 00:42:55.197
but only a few of them
actually get their ideas made.

925
00:42:55.990 --> 00:42:57.950
So Trudy just wanted to be careful...

926
00:42:58.117 --> 00:42:59.326
TERRY: Joy...

927
00:42:59.493 --> 00:43:03.372
I just wanted to let you know that
Touissant has almost finished his work.

928
00:43:03.539 --> 00:43:04.873
And, um...

929
00:43:04.957 --> 00:43:06.208
(both chuckle)

930
00:43:06.292 --> 00:43:08.627
You know, we really need to find
some more work for him.

931
00:43:08.794 --> 00:43:11.046
-JOY: You want more work in the house?
-Yeah.

932
00:43:11.130 --> 00:43:12.923
I have another big job I have to go to.

933
00:43:13.799 --> 00:43:15.301
-What?
-Yes.

934
00:43:15.467 --> 00:43:17.595
-Well, but we have real issues here.
-Sorry.

935
00:43:18.053 --> 00:43:20.180
-We don't have money for that work, Mom.
-Well...

936
00:43:20.806 --> 00:43:21.807
Okay.

937
00:43:23.017 --> 00:43:24.518
Joy...

938
00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:26.353
What is happening to you, Mother?

939
00:43:26.520 --> 00:43:28.188
TERRY: I don't know what's going on.

940
00:43:28.355 --> 00:43:29.940
Are you in love with Touissant?

941
00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:33.444
I was feeling alone.

942
00:43:34.903 --> 00:43:38.032
And I didn't even realize it, you know?

943
00:43:38.198 --> 00:43:39.366
And then...

944
00:43:44.788 --> 00:43:46.957
What did the patent search find?

945
00:43:48.208 --> 00:43:50.294
Trudy just wanted to be careful.

946
00:43:50.794 --> 00:43:53.213
And this guy found a man that's in Texas...

947
00:43:53.380 --> 00:43:55.966
who worked for another guy
in another country...

948
00:43:56.133 --> 00:44:00.971
where they have an idea
that might be similar to my mop.

949
00:44:01.138 --> 00:44:02.389
What country?

950
00:44:02.556 --> 00:44:03.557
Hong Kong.

951
00:44:04.016 --> 00:44:07.645
TRUDY: <i>The Hong Kong man</i>
<i>has a representative in Dallas, Texas.</i>

952
00:44:07.811 --> 00:44:11.482
<i>The Dallas man was very reasonable</i>
<i>with my lawyer.</i>

953
00:44:12.775 --> 00:44:13.817
JOY: Hey.

954
00:44:20.866 --> 00:44:22.451
TONY: So, this guy in Texas...

955
00:44:23.327 --> 00:44:27.039
We're supposed to pay him a royalty
on the patent as a protection, right?

956
00:44:27.122 --> 00:44:28.123
Right.

957
00:44:28.207 --> 00:44:29.708
-To be safe from any claims.
-Yeah.

958
00:44:29.875 --> 00:44:30.876
Is that correct?

959
00:44:31.043 --> 00:44:33.045
Please stop using the word "we."

960
00:44:33.212 --> 00:44:35.506
None of this is your money
or your business.

961
00:44:35.673 --> 00:44:39.426
But the same guy
also owns a manufacturing plant...

962
00:44:39.593 --> 00:44:42.554
that you guys say that
it's cheaper than any other place?

963
00:44:42.721 --> 00:44:44.306
-Yes. In California.
-RUDY: Yes.

964
00:44:44.473 --> 00:44:46.850
A metal and plastic injection mold factory.

965
00:44:47.017 --> 00:44:48.519
Okay, so it's the same guy.
He owns the patent...

966
00:44:48.602 --> 00:44:49.812
This happens all the time in business.

967
00:44:49.978 --> 00:44:52.231
You find the best partner. It's smart.

968
00:44:52.398 --> 00:44:54.650
He doesn't understand business.
He doesn't know business.

969
00:44:54.817 --> 00:44:55.984
TONY: No, no, I'm the first to say that.

970
00:44:56.068 --> 00:44:57.111
PEGGY: I understand business.

971
00:44:57.277 --> 00:45:00.531
Dad and I, we buy parts for the trucks
all the time at the garage.

972
00:45:00.698 --> 00:45:02.366
TRUDY: Morris did it all the time.

973
00:45:02.533 --> 00:45:04.535
One-stop shopping. It's the cheapest.

974
00:45:04.576 --> 00:45:06.412
-TONY: But is that normal?
-That's how he made his money.

975
00:45:06.453 --> 00:45:07.496
-Yeah, that's normal.
-Yes!

976
00:45:07.663 --> 00:45:09.331
But is it normal, the same guy
who has the patent...

977
00:45:09.498 --> 00:45:11.041
is the same guy
who has the manufacturing?

978
00:45:11.208 --> 00:45:12.418
-Yeah. Make it best.
-Yeah.

979
00:45:12.584 --> 00:45:14.420
-Yeah?
-Better if it's that way.

980
00:45:14.586 --> 00:45:16.588
TONY: And the lawyer?
Right? Morris's lawyer?

981
00:45:16.672 --> 00:45:18.799
RUDY: He's good. Let's not make trouble.
TRUDY: He's very good.

982
00:45:18.882 --> 00:45:22.720
But he specialized in garment business, no?
Not manufacturing business.

983
00:45:22.886 --> 00:45:26.473
Tony. Let's quit while we're ahead.

984
00:45:28.642 --> 00:45:32.896
I know that you want
Tony to be your counselor, if you will...

985
00:45:33.063 --> 00:45:34.982
and I will respect that...

986
00:45:35.149 --> 00:45:39.486
as Tony and you should respect
what we're proposing...

987
00:45:39.653 --> 00:45:42.990
as the lawyer
for this whole business endeavor.

988
00:45:47.661 --> 00:45:50.664
JOY: All right.
The parts have arrived from California...

989
00:45:50.831 --> 00:45:53.083
and we can start manufacturing here.

990
00:45:53.625 --> 00:45:55.961
I have the first assembled mop.

991
00:45:56.628 --> 00:45:58.922
I told you it was gonna be more refined.

992
00:45:59.715 --> 00:46:00.924
And it is.

993
00:46:02.301 --> 00:46:03.302
PEGGY: Father Martinez is here.

994
00:46:03.469 --> 00:46:05.679
You need to set those women up right now
and get going.

995
00:46:06.180 --> 00:46:07.890
They're gonna be so grateful
for the jobs, Joy.

996
00:46:08.056 --> 00:46:09.558
Okay. All right.
I'll go talk to those ladies.

997
00:46:09.725 --> 00:46:11.977
Now I finally have jobs for them.

998
00:46:14.897 --> 00:46:16.482
(all speaking Spanish)

999
00:46:43.926 --> 00:46:45.969
And I'll show you guys how to assemble...

1000
00:46:46.053 --> 00:46:48.263
(all speaking Spanish)

1001
00:47:08.867 --> 00:47:11.036
I'm a little proud of you.
I gotta admit it.

1002
00:47:12.246 --> 00:47:17.584
But, it costs much more than $15,000
to make the first run.

1003
00:47:17.751 --> 00:47:18.794
I know, Trudy.

1004
00:47:18.961 --> 00:47:21.129
But with all due respect,
that actually wasn't my fault.

1005
00:47:21.505 --> 00:47:23.465
RUDY: Look at this. More bills.

1006
00:47:25.509 --> 00:47:27.928
-What?
-TRUDY: Another bill from Gerhardt.

1007
00:47:28.095 --> 00:47:30.681
This guy keeps billing me
for his mistakes.

1008
00:47:30.848 --> 00:47:32.808
-TRUDY: That's business.
-No.

1009
00:47:32.975 --> 00:47:34.643
That's not the way I do business.

1010
00:47:34.810 --> 00:47:36.311
I'm calling this guy.

1011
00:47:41.692 --> 00:47:43.652
Gerhardt, I'm not gonna
keep paying for these parts...

1012
00:47:43.819 --> 00:47:45.320
that it's taking you four times to get right.

1013
00:47:45.487 --> 00:47:48.365
GERHARDT: That was your design.
You have to pay for those parts.

1014
00:47:48.532 --> 00:47:51.285
That's mold-making.
That's the process.

1015
00:47:51.451 --> 00:47:53.704
My clients pay when we figure it out.

1016
00:47:53.871 --> 00:47:55.455
It was not my design, Gerhardt.

1017
00:47:55.622 --> 00:47:58.000
It was your mistake. I'm not paying it.

1018
00:47:58.166 --> 00:48:00.586
That was your design.
You have to pay.

1019
00:48:00.752 --> 00:48:02.588
TRUDY: Did you just hang up on him?

1020
00:48:02.754 --> 00:48:06.049
This guy was supposed to be easy
and inexpensive.

1021
00:48:06.216 --> 00:48:08.844
He keeps overbilling us.
I'm not paying for it.

1022
00:48:10.429 --> 00:48:12.681
Nobody pay it.

1023
00:48:12.848 --> 00:48:14.892
I'm gonna fight it out with this guy.

1024
00:48:15.058 --> 00:48:17.853
Just assemble them and try to sell them.

1025
00:48:18.228 --> 00:48:20.564
Just put it in your window.
Let your customers decide.

1026
00:48:20.731 --> 00:48:22.149
My family's been going to you
my whole life.

1027
00:48:22.316 --> 00:48:25.277
Look, the big companies,
they pay me for my shelf space.

1028
00:48:25.736 --> 00:48:28.196
Maybe you can sell one of your mops
to those big companies.

1029
00:48:28.363 --> 00:48:30.991
And maybe they'll put it on my shelf.

1030
00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:36.538
JOY: <i>It's expensive, at $19.95,</i>
<i>but it's the only mop you'll ever have to buy.</i>

1031
00:48:36.705 --> 00:48:40.834
But I don't want people
to buy one mop for $20...

1032
00:48:41.001 --> 00:48:42.628
and never have to buy another mop again.

1033
00:48:42.794 --> 00:48:47.758
I'd rather they keep buying our mops at $5,
50 times, 100 times.

1034
00:48:48.634 --> 00:48:53.055
Look, you were broke and bored.
You had an idea.

1035
00:48:53.221 --> 00:48:55.390
So what? Lots of people have ideas.

1036
00:48:55.849 --> 00:48:58.518
Go home.
Please, take care of your family.

1037
00:48:59.645 --> 00:49:01.438
JOY: <i>Hi. Would you like to try a new mop?</i>

1038
00:49:02.064 --> 00:49:04.149
It's the only mop
you'll ever have to buy.

1039
00:49:05.859 --> 00:49:08.028
-Hi. Would you like to try a new mop?
-WOMAN 1: No.

1040
00:49:08.195 --> 00:49:09.404
It's self-wringing.

1041
00:49:09.571 --> 00:49:11.865
You can remove the mop head,
throw it in the washing machine.

1042
00:49:12.032 --> 00:49:13.075
-No germs.
-No.

1043
00:49:13.241 --> 00:49:14.576
No.

1044
00:49:14.660 --> 00:49:16.286
-No?
-WOMAN 2: Look at that.

1045
00:49:16.453 --> 00:49:18.372
You want to just try it?
You could just try.

1046
00:49:18.538 --> 00:49:21.667
It can self-wring. See?
No other mop does this.

1047
00:49:23.001 --> 00:49:24.795
(sighs)

1048
00:49:42.854 --> 00:49:45.315
Come and try the brand-new mop!

1049
00:49:46.525 --> 00:49:48.402
-It's the mop of the future.
-WOMAN 3: No, thanks.

1050
00:49:49.444 --> 00:49:50.696
JACKIE: Want to try this mop, ladies?

1051
00:49:50.862 --> 00:49:51.989
-What's this?
-Hey, miss.

1052
00:49:52.155 --> 00:49:53.407
It's a brand-new mop.

1053
00:49:53.490 --> 00:49:54.574
Oh.

1054
00:49:54.658 --> 00:49:56.493
You could wring it
without getting your hands dirty.

1055
00:49:56.660 --> 00:49:57.703
I don't think so.

1056
00:49:57.869 --> 00:50:00.747
Come on. Try it.
It's the mop of the future.

1057
00:50:00.831 --> 00:50:01.832
(exhales)

1058
00:50:02.541 --> 00:50:04.543
-Self-wringing, huh?
-Yeah.

1059
00:50:04.710 --> 00:50:07.004
All right. I do like the idea of that.

1060
00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:11.008
I hate having to touch the mop head
after I get done cleaning the bathroom floor.

1061
00:50:11.174 --> 00:50:12.426
I always think that's disgusting,
you know?

1062
00:50:12.592 --> 00:50:13.635
WOMAN 4: It's so gross.

1063
00:50:13.802 --> 00:50:17.764
Wow. It really does get all the corners
that my sponge mop won't get.

1064
00:50:17.973 --> 00:50:21.143
All those crannies
where my kids spill their juice.

1065
00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:24.104
I really like it. Can we buy it?

1066
00:50:24.271 --> 00:50:25.689
-Take it easy, Cristy.
-(women laugh)

1067
00:50:26.023 --> 00:50:29.026
Wow. I mean, that's just amazing.
You really don't have to touch it.

1068
00:50:29.192 --> 00:50:30.193
Look at that.

1069
00:50:30.360 --> 00:50:31.570
You know what would make this perfect...

1070
00:50:31.737 --> 00:50:34.031
if you could remove the mop head,
put it in the washing machine...

1071
00:50:34.197 --> 00:50:35.866
-Really get it clean.
-WOMAN 5: That'd be great.

1072
00:50:36.616 --> 00:50:37.701
-You can.
-WOMAN 5: What?

1073
00:50:37.868 --> 00:50:38.869
Are you serious?

1074
00:50:39.036 --> 00:50:41.204
-Well how much is this mop?
-JACKIE: It's $19.95.

1075
00:50:41.371 --> 00:50:42.372
WOMAN 6: No, that's too much.

1076
00:50:42.539 --> 00:50:44.082
JOY: But I guess, I mean,
if it is the only mop

1077
00:50:44.166 --> 00:50:45.208
that you ever have to buy...

1078
00:50:45.375 --> 00:50:46.376
I mean we keep buying those
$5 mops.

1079
00:50:46.543 --> 00:50:47.753
-Hi, Daddy.
-TONY: Hi, sweetie.

1080
00:50:47.919 --> 00:50:52.841
You, you remember Angela?
And her two brothers, right?

1081
00:50:53.008 --> 00:50:54.676
I do. Hello.

1082
00:50:54.843 --> 00:50:56.553
-CRISTY: Mommy, the policeman.
-Ma'am?

1083
00:50:56.720 --> 00:50:57.846
CRISTY: Did we break the law?

1084
00:50:58.013 --> 00:51:00.223
-I'm taking this merchandise.
-No, no. We're leaving. We're leaving.

1085
00:51:00.390 --> 00:51:01.975
Now, I'm gonna let you off with a warning.

1086
00:51:02.142 --> 00:51:03.435
We were just leaving. No. Sir...

1087
00:51:03.602 --> 00:51:05.312
If the customers can just see
what the mop can do...

1088
00:51:05.437 --> 00:51:07.105
But if I catch you out here again,
you will be prosecuted!

1089
00:51:07.272 --> 00:51:08.356
Well, where do I go?
Sir, please!

1090
00:51:08.440 --> 00:51:09.441
You cannot sell on Kmart property!

1091
00:51:09.524 --> 00:51:11.026
I made those mops myself.
I paid for them. Please.

1092
00:51:11.109 --> 00:51:12.319
JACKIE: It took a lot of work.

1093
00:51:12.402 --> 00:51:13.445
-I won't come back,
-(Cristy sobbing)

1094
00:51:13.528 --> 00:51:14.571
but you don't have to take my stuff!

1095
00:51:14.654 --> 00:51:15.697
Please!

1096
00:51:15.864 --> 00:51:18.075
-Are you even allowed to do this?
-How embarrassing for you...

1097
00:51:18.158 --> 00:51:19.618
to be seen here like this
with your daughter.

1098
00:51:19.701 --> 00:51:21.870
-What kind of parent are you, huh?
-MAN: Yeah, Tony.

1099
00:51:21.953 --> 00:51:22.996
-TONY: Enough.
-Hey.

1100
00:51:23.080 --> 00:51:24.122
TONY: Hey, hey, guys. Guys...

1101
00:51:24.206 --> 00:51:25.248
MAN 1: All right.
MAN 2: Come on.

1102
00:51:25.332 --> 00:51:26.541
-Let's go.
-Tony, let's go.

1103
00:51:26.708 --> 00:51:28.293
Yeah, I'm coming. I'm coming.

1104
00:51:38.178 --> 00:51:39.221
(Cristy crying)

1105
00:51:39.304 --> 00:51:42.140
JACKIE: Cristy, honey, it's okay.
Your mommy's okay.

1106
00:51:44.017 --> 00:51:45.102
(grunts)

1107
00:51:45.685 --> 00:51:48.855
This stupid thing.
This place is falling apart!

1108
00:51:49.022 --> 00:51:50.607
No... No.

1109
00:51:52.609 --> 00:51:54.528
TERRY: Honey, the telephone isn't working.

1110
00:51:54.694 --> 00:51:56.071
I know. I just got the notice.

1111
00:51:56.238 --> 00:51:59.449
I had to go next door to use the phone.
Tommy's got a fever.

1112
00:51:59.616 --> 00:52:00.617
Tommy has a fever?

1113
00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:03.578
Simple cold with a cough.
It's going around. All the kids have it.

1114
00:52:03.745 --> 00:52:05.122
Thank God the heat's still working.

1115
00:52:05.288 --> 00:52:07.457
Mommy, why isn't the phone working?

1116
00:52:07.624 --> 00:52:09.126
Because I'm late on paying the bill.

1117
00:52:09.209 --> 00:52:10.252
(Cristy coughing)

1118
00:52:10.335 --> 00:52:11.920
-Are we gonna lose our house?
-Not you too.

1119
00:52:12.087 --> 00:52:13.672
No, we're not gonna lose our house.

1120
00:52:14.756 --> 00:52:16.216
Come on. Get upstairs. Get in the bath.

1121
00:52:16.383 --> 00:52:17.717
Listen to your mom and get
right in that tub.

1122
00:52:17.884 --> 00:52:19.553
-I don't want a hot bath.
-I don't care.

1123
00:52:19.636 --> 00:52:21.847
Cristy, you get in that hot bath.
Listen to your mother.

1124
00:52:21.930 --> 00:52:23.849
I don't want you getting sick too.

1125
00:52:24.516 --> 00:52:28.186
Lauren Wells said you're a cleaning lady
and sell used mops.

1126
00:52:28.270 --> 00:52:29.312
(sighs)

1127
00:52:29.855 --> 00:52:31.565
Lauren Wells said that?

1128
00:52:32.607 --> 00:52:35.318
Yeah. And it really hurt my feelings.

1129
00:52:35.986 --> 00:52:39.239
First of all, even if I was
a cleaning lady, so what?

1130
00:52:39.406 --> 00:52:41.199
There's no shame in hard work.

1131
00:52:42.576 --> 00:52:44.411
And second of all, you know, I'm...

1132
00:52:46.079 --> 00:52:49.624
I'm trying to sell a new mop,
not used mops.

1133
00:52:50.250 --> 00:52:55.463
And third of all,
don't take any guff from anybody.

1134
00:52:55.964 --> 00:52:59.176
You know, don't let it in.

1135
00:52:59.926 --> 00:53:02.971
I know it's hard.
And I'm sorry that happened.

1136
00:53:04.598 --> 00:53:05.891
Now get in the bath.

1137
00:53:09.728 --> 00:53:11.646
(Tommy coughing)

1138
00:53:12.647 --> 00:53:13.690
JOY: Oh...

1139
00:53:13.773 --> 00:53:15.567
Come on. Go to sleep, honey.

1140
00:53:15.650 --> 00:53:17.068
(kisses)

1141
00:53:21.281 --> 00:53:22.574
(sighs)

1142
00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:31.166
Joy?

1143
00:53:31.458 --> 00:53:32.792
Not now, Mimi.

1144
00:53:32.959 --> 00:53:35.879
Joy, wait, wait.
Just tell me what happened today.

1145
00:53:36.046 --> 00:53:38.423
I want to know how it went.
Please, I want to know.

1146
00:53:40.675 --> 00:53:42.093
It was a disaster.

1147
00:53:43.011 --> 00:53:44.095
But you must never give up.

1148
00:53:44.262 --> 00:53:45.847
Ever since you were little,
you were born to bear...

1149
00:53:46.014 --> 00:53:48.266
Born to bear what, Mimi?

1150
00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:51.561
Failure? Disgrace?

1151
00:53:52.771 --> 00:53:55.023
Humiliation in front of my daughter?

1152
00:53:55.815 --> 00:53:59.819
You were born to be
the unanxious presence in the room.

1153
00:53:59.986 --> 00:54:02.864
And I know that I'm gonna live
to see you grow...

1154
00:54:03.031 --> 00:54:06.284
to be the successful matriarch
that you were born to be.

1155
00:54:06.451 --> 00:54:07.494
-Matriarch...
-(doorbell rings)

1156
00:54:08.745 --> 00:54:09.996
To be a mother with courage.

1157
00:54:10.163 --> 00:54:12.040
Who can't even support her children.

1158
00:54:12.457 --> 00:54:13.541
MIMI: Sweetheart.

1159
00:54:17.504 --> 00:54:19.339
What are you doing here?

1160
00:54:19.506 --> 00:54:21.132
TONY: I have this idea.

1161
00:54:21.299 --> 00:54:22.884
-A guy I know.
-What guy?

1162
00:54:23.051 --> 00:54:28.056
He used to work with me.
And now he works at this big retailer.

1163
00:54:28.223 --> 00:54:30.433
A new way of doing business.

1164
00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:32.394
I mean, it's worth a try.

1165
00:54:33.770 --> 00:54:35.689
You would do that for me?

1166
00:54:35.855 --> 00:54:36.982
Of course.

1167
00:54:37.148 --> 00:54:39.609
MIMI: <i>They were the best divorced couple</i>
<i>in America.</i>

1168
00:54:40.568 --> 00:54:43.280
<i>Much better friends than</i>
<i>they were husband and wife.</i>

1169
00:54:44.197 --> 00:54:45.740
I can get you a meeting with him.

1170
00:54:48.201 --> 00:54:49.536
Where is it?

1171
00:54:52.831 --> 00:54:55.250
JOY: But I don't understand
what we're doing in Amish country.

1172
00:54:55.333 --> 00:54:58.044
They don't even have electricity out here.
How could they sell anything on TV?

1173
00:54:58.128 --> 00:55:00.422
It has nothing to do with Amish people.

1174
00:55:00.547 --> 00:55:03.008
It just happens to be located here.
I looked it up.

1175
00:55:03.174 --> 00:55:04.759
In Amish country.

1176
00:55:04.926 --> 00:55:06.636
-Amish.
-What?

1177
00:55:06.803 --> 00:55:08.805
-Amish.
-Amish.

1178
00:55:20.859 --> 00:55:22.193
Sign in, please.

1179
00:55:24.029 --> 00:55:26.656
We're here to see Marv Brickman.

1180
00:55:27.282 --> 00:55:28.450
Okay.

1181
00:55:28.616 --> 00:55:32.162
Marv Brickman, does he know who you are
if I call his office?

1182
00:55:32.829 --> 00:55:33.872
Of course he knows.

1183
00:55:33.997 --> 00:55:35.749
We're friends. We used to work together.

1184
00:55:35.832 --> 00:55:37.459
(phone ringing)

1185
00:55:37.542 --> 00:55:39.169
RECEPTIONIST: QVC, please hold.

1186
00:55:48.345 --> 00:55:50.347
-(door opens)
-(men laughing)

1187
00:55:50.430 --> 00:55:52.974
MAN: But Tom was wrong about that.
He was wrong about the numbers...

1188
00:55:57.145 --> 00:55:58.229
MARV: Tony.

1189
00:55:58.396 --> 00:55:59.564
TONY: Marv. How are you?

1190
00:55:59.731 --> 00:56:01.107
MARV: I can't see you today.

1191
00:56:01.274 --> 00:56:02.525
TONY: Why?

1192
00:56:02.692 --> 00:56:04.569
MARV: Maybe tomorrow
if you can stay in town.

1193
00:56:04.736 --> 00:56:07.030
TONY: No, we left the kids at home.
We can't.

1194
00:56:07.197 --> 00:56:08.990
We can't stay until tomorrow.

1195
00:56:09.157 --> 00:56:12.118
MARV: Listen, you can't just expect
to come in here and see someone.

1196
00:56:12.285 --> 00:56:13.787
NEIL: Hey, did you take care
of that advertising thing?

1197
00:56:13.870 --> 00:56:15.789
MARV: Yes, I did.
NEIL: Good. All right.

1198
00:56:15.872 --> 00:56:16.915
What's going on here?

1199
00:56:16.998 --> 00:56:19.167
MARV: This is my good friend, Tony.
TONY: Tony Miranda.

1200
00:56:19.250 --> 00:56:20.377
MARV: We worked together at Campbell's.

1201
00:56:20.460 --> 00:56:21.503
NEIL: Neil Walker.

1202
00:56:21.586 --> 00:56:23.129
MARV: And this is his ex-wife.
NEIL: Good to meet you.

1203
00:56:23.380 --> 00:56:24.589
-Joy.
-Hi. Neil.

1204
00:56:24.756 --> 00:56:25.799
MARV: She's an inventor.

1205
00:56:25.965 --> 00:56:27.300
She wanted two minutes
of your time today,

1206
00:56:27.384 --> 00:56:28.968
but, Neil, don't worry about this.

1207
00:56:29.135 --> 00:56:30.428
-Maybe tomorrow.
-NEIL: You know what?

1208
00:56:30.595 --> 00:56:33.223
Why don't you come in for five minutes
while the sales group's still here.

1209
00:56:33.390 --> 00:56:34.808
-Okay. Hold my bag.
-MARV: Neil, are you sure?

1210
00:56:34.974 --> 00:56:36.184
TONY: Yeah.
NEIL: Yeah, absolutely.

1211
00:56:36.351 --> 00:56:37.602
TONY: Thank you.

1212
00:56:37.769 --> 00:56:38.812
NEIL: Got everything?
JOY: Yeah.

1213
00:56:38.978 --> 00:56:40.438
Great. Thank you, man.

1214
00:56:41.481 --> 00:56:42.565
Thank you.

1215
00:56:50.657 --> 00:56:52.325
So tell us your name, please.

1216
00:56:56.121 --> 00:56:57.247
I'm Joy.

1217
00:56:59.374 --> 00:57:01.251
And what would you like
to show us today?

1218
00:57:01.418 --> 00:57:03.503
I have a self-wringing mop.

1219
00:57:03.586 --> 00:57:04.712
Mmm.

1220
00:57:05.255 --> 00:57:07.048
-Just...
-Do you need some help?

1221
00:57:07.215 --> 00:57:08.383
-JOY: No. No, no.
-(water splashing)

1222
00:57:08.883 --> 00:57:10.301
-All right.
-(water spills)

1223
00:57:11.052 --> 00:57:12.846
-MAN: Uh, that's my shoe.
-(people laughing)

1224
00:57:12.929 --> 00:57:14.764
JOY: Oh, my goodness. I am so sorry, sir.

1225
00:57:17.016 --> 00:57:18.435
MAN: Sock's wet.

1226
00:57:18.601 --> 00:57:19.769
JOY: Do you mind?

1227
00:57:20.979 --> 00:57:22.021
Sorry.

1228
00:57:25.733 --> 00:57:26.818
Is that plastic?

1229
00:57:26.943 --> 00:57:28.027
JOY: Yes.

1230
00:57:28.153 --> 00:57:30.029
Arnold, why don't you give it a try?
Is that okay?

1231
00:57:30.196 --> 00:57:31.364
JOY: Yes, of course.

1232
00:57:31.948 --> 00:57:33.116
-Just dunk it.
-(man laughing)

1233
00:57:33.283 --> 00:57:34.784
-I dip it?
-Yes.

1234
00:57:35.201 --> 00:57:37.454
And then I... twist it?

1235
00:57:37.495 --> 00:57:38.580
JOY: But you pull...
You have to pull it first.

1236
00:57:38.663 --> 00:57:39.706
-Pull it and twist it.
-(all laughing)

1237
00:57:39.789 --> 00:57:40.874
You got to pull it first before you twist it.

1238
00:57:40.957 --> 00:57:42.000
-I'm pulling it and...
-Pull and twist.

1239
00:57:42.083 --> 00:57:43.126
...and I am twisting it.

1240
00:57:43.877 --> 00:57:45.420
MAN: Pull and twist,
just like when you're on the road.

1241
00:57:45.628 --> 00:57:47.255
(all laughing)

1242
00:57:47.755 --> 00:57:51.259
We don't mean to be disrespectful, Joy.
It's the end of a long day for us.

1243
00:57:52.594 --> 00:57:55.889
I feel like I want to tell you
a little bit about who I am.

1244
00:57:56.055 --> 00:57:59.350
Because I have a feeling you don't know
exactly where you are right now.

1245
00:57:59.434 --> 00:58:00.477
Am I right?

1246
00:58:02.145 --> 00:58:03.480
Ten months ago...

1247
00:58:03.646 --> 00:58:07.150
a man named Barry Diller
called me from Los Angeles.

1248
00:58:08.067 --> 00:58:12.030
He started a television network.
Fox television channel.

1249
00:58:12.530 --> 00:58:16.784
And prior to that, he ran 20th Century Fox,
among other studios.

1250
00:58:17.452 --> 00:58:20.079
And he acquired a little cable channel...

1251
00:58:20.246 --> 00:58:22.665
right here in Lancaster, Pennsylvania.

1252
00:58:22.832 --> 00:58:24.792
And he hired me to run it...

1253
00:58:25.502 --> 00:58:27.587
as a bigger idea.

1254
00:58:29.839 --> 00:58:31.758
Now, I'm from Detroit, Michigan.

1255
00:58:33.218 --> 00:58:37.639
I ran America's largest, most affordable...

1256
00:58:37.805 --> 00:58:40.642
successful, value-driven retailer.

1257
00:58:40.808 --> 00:58:42.602
Chain called Kmart.

1258
00:58:43.186 --> 00:58:46.064
Prior to that, I was a buyer for Kmart.

1259
00:58:46.731 --> 00:58:51.194
And prior to that,
I managed seven separate Kmart stores.

1260
00:58:51.653 --> 00:58:54.906
I decide what products
we let into our stores here...

1261
00:58:55.073 --> 00:59:00.078
into people's homes, 24 hours a day,
for our valued customers.

1262
00:59:01.329 --> 00:59:05.291
I choose very carefully
and very conservatively.

1263
00:59:06.251 --> 00:59:10.421
I spend most of my day deflecting
incoming shots from people like yourself.

1264
00:59:13.132 --> 00:59:14.175
You see that chart?

1265
00:59:20.848 --> 00:59:24.894
This green line either rises
or stays the same each month.

1266
00:59:25.812 --> 00:59:28.565
There's no problem
with my product choice.

1267
00:59:30.066 --> 00:59:32.694
Do you know what QVC stands for, Joy?

1268
00:59:34.571 --> 00:59:35.738
No, I don't.

1269
00:59:36.531 --> 00:59:39.867
Quality, Value, Convenience.

1270
00:59:41.661 --> 00:59:44.831
I sell product affordably,
but I don't sell cheap product.

1271
00:59:44.998 --> 00:59:47.417
And your mop is plastic
and it looks strange.

1272
00:59:49.919 --> 00:59:52.338
I don't know anything about charts.

1273
00:59:52.505 --> 00:59:53.548
Or...

1274
00:59:55.216 --> 00:59:56.968
...business, frankly.

1275
00:59:57.760 --> 00:59:59.762
But I do clean my own home.

1276
01:00:00.847 --> 01:00:02.765
And I made this mop...

1277
01:00:02.932 --> 01:00:06.102
because it is better
than anything else out there.

1278
01:00:09.355 --> 01:00:10.982
Please give me a chance.

1279
01:00:13.276 --> 01:00:14.611
I like that it's plastic...

1280
01:00:14.777 --> 01:00:17.739
because it's so light in my hands,
it's like nothing.

1281
01:00:18.573 --> 01:00:21.659
It's also ten times more absorbent
than any other mop on the market.

1282
01:00:21.784 --> 01:00:22.827
Why?

1283
01:00:23.661 --> 01:00:28.499
Because of 300 feet of continuous
cotton loop that I looped myself.

1284
01:00:28.666 --> 01:00:31.377
That is an enormous amount
of absorbent cotton...

1285
01:00:31.544 --> 01:00:33.254
on a very small mop head.

1286
01:00:33.421 --> 01:00:36.883
Now I'm done with the bathroom,
and I haven't wrung the mop once.

1287
01:00:37.050 --> 01:00:38.676
Let me ask you a question.

1288
01:00:39.510 --> 01:00:40.845
Would you take this mop...

1289
01:00:41.012 --> 01:00:42.305
where you were
just cleaning the bathroom...

1290
01:00:42.472 --> 01:00:44.390
and around the toilet,
and all of those germs...

1291
01:00:44.766 --> 01:00:46.934
and take it into the kitchen...

1292
01:00:47.101 --> 01:00:49.562
where your family eats,
where you feed your children?

1293
01:00:50.813 --> 01:00:53.775
I take this mop head,
I put it in the washing machine...

1294
01:00:53.941 --> 01:00:55.568
it comes out clean like new.

1295
01:00:56.611 --> 01:01:00.073
You can't do that with any other mop.

1296
01:01:00.531 --> 01:01:02.033
-So...
-Stop.

1297
01:01:06.037 --> 01:01:09.374
Can you make 50,000
of these mops by next week?

1298
01:01:11.626 --> 01:01:13.211
Yeah, I think so.

1299
01:01:15.213 --> 01:01:17.632
NEIL: David Selznick,
the son of immigrants...

1300
01:01:17.882 --> 01:01:20.927
married Jennifer Jones from Oklahoma,
America's sweetheart.

1301
01:01:21.094 --> 01:01:23.304
That just goes to show you
that in America...

1302
01:01:23.471 --> 01:01:27.225
the ordinary meets the extraordinary
every single day.

1303
01:01:27.892 --> 01:01:29.560
Thomas. Where are you going with that?

1304
01:01:29.727 --> 01:01:31.270
The skinny pants you wanted.

1305
01:01:31.437 --> 01:01:33.981
NEIL: I never said "skinny pants."
I said, "stovepipe." Classic look.

1306
01:01:34.148 --> 01:01:35.483
(stammers) I heard "skinny pants."

1307
01:01:35.733 --> 01:01:37.819
You know how much I love the stovepipe.

1308
01:01:37.985 --> 01:01:39.737
-Stovepipe. Classic. Got it.
-Got it.

1309
01:01:39.946 --> 01:01:41.614
-Fine, we'll go for stovepipe.
-Thank you.

1310
01:01:43.282 --> 01:01:47.078
See those guys? I told them so many times
and they still don't understand.

1311
01:01:47.245 --> 01:01:48.996
A very smart guy once said...

1312
01:01:49.163 --> 01:01:50.832
"You tell somebody something
once, they don't listen.

1313
01:01:50.915 --> 01:01:52.458
"You tell somebody four times,
they don't listen.

1314
01:01:52.625 --> 01:01:55.628
"By the ninth time you say it,
they begin to hear you."

1315
01:01:55.795 --> 01:01:57.588
That's why we're on 24 hours a day.

1316
01:01:57.755 --> 01:02:00.174
That's why, with the people who I have
to tell about the stovepipe.

1317
01:02:01.592 --> 01:02:03.094
Music in the makeup rooms?

1318
01:02:03.261 --> 01:02:04.595
Yeah, I thought it'd
give a sense of place, Todd.

1319
01:02:04.762 --> 01:02:06.973
But if you don't want it,
you can always turn it down.

1320
01:02:07.140 --> 01:02:08.182
You're our biggest seller, Todd.

1321
01:02:08.349 --> 01:02:10.435
Whatever you need
to make you comfortable.

1322
01:02:10.601 --> 01:02:12.061
You're who we care about.
You're our number-one seller.

1323
01:02:12.103 --> 01:02:13.312
-CINDY: What?
-Oh, no.

1324
01:02:14.188 --> 01:02:15.606
He's your number-one seller?

1325
01:02:15.773 --> 01:02:18.943
No, no, no. Cindy, please.
You know that we love you.

1326
01:02:19.277 --> 01:02:21.028
-(door slams)
-Oh, for heaven sake.

1327
01:02:21.362 --> 01:02:25.450
She's never had a professional attitude.
Clearly, she's jealous.

1328
01:02:25.783 --> 01:02:27.618
But could you do me a favor?
Make her your friend.

1329
01:02:27.785 --> 01:02:30.997
Could you just do me that favor, Todd?
Please?

1330
01:02:31.164 --> 01:02:32.165
For me?

1331
01:02:32.999 --> 01:02:34.125
-Yes, sir.
-Thank you.

1332
01:02:34.292 --> 01:02:36.127
This is Joy. She has
a very exciting new mop

1333
01:02:36.210 --> 01:02:37.462
that we're gonna introduce next week.

1334
01:02:37.795 --> 01:02:39.797
I would like you to launch it.
You're my first choice.

1335
01:02:39.964 --> 01:02:41.215
A mop?

1336
01:02:41.382 --> 01:02:44.886
You want me to bring this
newborn into the world?

1337
01:02:45.803 --> 01:02:51.225
That newborn that you're holding is
every cent, every dollar, even debt...

1338
01:02:51.392 --> 01:02:52.393
that I've ever made.

1339
01:02:52.977 --> 01:02:54.312
Every cent you've ever made?

1340
01:02:54.645 --> 01:02:55.646
That's right.

1341
01:02:55.730 --> 01:02:57.815
That kind of pressure is not helpful.

1342
01:02:58.191 --> 01:02:59.650
-What?
-No.

1343
01:02:59.817 --> 01:03:01.986
It's not part of my process, either.

1344
01:03:02.403 --> 01:03:03.571
Oh.

1345
01:03:03.863 --> 01:03:07.241
-NEIL: Todd...
-I didn't mean to pressure you, Todd.

1346
01:03:09.160 --> 01:03:11.412
-NEIL: Performers can be finicky creatures.
-He's very sensitive.

1347
01:03:11.704 --> 01:03:14.999
He is our number-one seller.
He is selling everything through the roof

1348
01:03:15.208 --> 01:03:17.376
in numbers we've never seen before.

1349
01:03:17.835 --> 01:03:18.920
I take it very seriously.

1350
01:03:19.086 --> 01:03:21.172
I see it as a privilege that we have
to go into people's homes.

1351
01:03:21.339 --> 01:03:23.007
And I despise anybody
who's cynical about that.

1352
01:03:23.174 --> 01:03:26.511
Jack Warner wasn't cynical about that.
Darryl Zanuck wasn't cynical about that.

1353
01:03:26.677 --> 01:03:28.346
And Neil Walker is not cynical about that.

1354
01:03:28.513 --> 01:03:30.389
Let me show you the stage.

1355
01:03:31.682 --> 01:03:33.601
I believe eventually, one day...

1356
01:03:33.768 --> 01:03:38.606
television will even be
by and about actual regular people.

1357
01:03:38.773 --> 01:03:42.026
Maybe even on computers,
24 hours a day.

1358
01:03:42.235 --> 01:03:44.737
Who knows?
Nobody thought this network would be real.

1359
01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:47.698
-And here we are.
-(rumbling)

1360
01:03:47.907 --> 01:03:50.076
-By the way, stock's going through the roof.
-What...?

1361
01:03:50.868 --> 01:03:52.370
(dog barking)

1362
01:03:52.453 --> 01:03:53.913
Must be mindful of Joan's dog.

1363
01:03:54.080 --> 01:03:55.915
Who's... Oh.

1364
01:03:56.040 --> 01:03:57.208
-Who's Joan?
-(gasps)

1365
01:03:58.042 --> 01:04:00.294
Thank you, darling.

1366
01:04:01.087 --> 01:04:04.090
Oh, you're never gonna make it
in a man's world dressed like that.

1367
01:04:04.257 --> 01:04:06.717
Oh, Mr. Peepers, you were
almost a Peepers pancake.

1368
01:04:06.884 --> 01:04:10.555
NEIL: It's a round stage that has four
or five different sets that rotate...

1369
01:04:10.721 --> 01:04:13.391
depending on what we're selling
at a given moment.

1370
01:04:13.558 --> 01:04:14.809
JOAN: The clasp is part
of the necklace. See?

1371
01:04:14.976 --> 01:04:17.603
Look at the quality in this glass.
That's what we do.

1372
01:04:17.728 --> 01:04:19.063
CINDY: Absolutely exquisite.

1373
01:04:19.105 --> 01:04:22.316
Here comes Joan and Cindy.
Watch this.

1374
01:04:23.067 --> 01:04:24.235
These guys are major.

1375
01:04:24.569 --> 01:04:25.903
Joan's the original seller.

1376
01:04:26.070 --> 01:04:27.738
JOAN: If you're just starting
your jewelry wardrobe,

1377
01:04:27.822 --> 01:04:29.240
can you do anything better than this?

1378
01:04:29.407 --> 01:04:31.909
You're gonna mix in your blacks,
your golds, your pearls.

1379
01:04:32.076 --> 01:04:33.077
-Everything.
-Everything.

1380
01:04:33.119 --> 01:04:34.412
Look at it against the peach. Okay?

1381
01:04:34.579 --> 01:04:36.080
-Look at that.
-Morning.

1382
01:04:36.247 --> 01:04:37.665
-Look at that.
-Green. Afternoon.

1383
01:04:37.832 --> 01:04:39.292
-Look. Black, night.
-Black, evening.

1384
01:04:39.458 --> 01:04:41.669
-Of course at night.
-I mean, can you be more elegant?

1385
01:04:41.836 --> 01:04:44.005
So it's functional. Elegant.

1386
01:04:44.171 --> 01:04:46.757
You can wear it alone.
You can wear it... What I love...

1387
01:04:46.924 --> 01:04:48.926
See. Stars and people,
they always make the mistake.

1388
01:04:49.093 --> 01:04:51.012
They think it's about the face,
but it's not.

1389
01:04:51.178 --> 01:04:52.597
It's about the hands.

1390
01:04:52.763 --> 01:04:54.098
Because that's what people use.

1391
01:04:54.265 --> 01:04:55.933
They hold things they care about.

1392
01:04:56.017 --> 01:04:58.436
And her hands are gonna become
their hands.

1393
01:04:58.603 --> 01:04:59.770
And that becomes them.

1394
01:04:59.937 --> 01:05:02.273
And then their voice,
and then their eyes.

1395
01:05:02.440 --> 01:05:03.983
Stars always make the mistake.

1396
01:05:04.358 --> 01:05:07.486
It's really about the hands and the voice.
That's the heart of it.

1397
01:05:08.362 --> 01:05:10.615
Number J-6276.

1398
01:05:10.948 --> 01:05:12.199
A $100 value.

1399
01:05:12.366 --> 01:05:13.784
Are they not phenomenal?

1400
01:05:14.452 --> 01:05:16.120
-Now watch this.
-CINDY: These can be yours.

1401
01:05:16.287 --> 01:05:18.831
Cindy's gonna lay this down right...

1402
01:05:18.998 --> 01:05:20.124
CINDY: $39.99.

1403
01:05:20.291 --> 01:05:21.459
...now!

1404
01:05:22.001 --> 01:05:23.961
You need this. You can get this.

1405
01:05:24.128 --> 01:05:25.630
You need to call right now, though.

1406
01:05:26.172 --> 01:05:27.298
I'm being told we have limited quantity left.

1407
01:05:27.340 --> 01:05:28.466
NEIL: Watch the calls come in.

1408
01:05:28.633 --> 01:05:30.301
Watch them. Here they come.

1409
01:05:30.468 --> 01:05:32.887
CINDY: For $39.99,
you might as well get several.

1410
01:05:33.054 --> 01:05:35.222
-Calls coming in now.
-(indistinct chattering)

1411
01:05:35.389 --> 01:05:37.058
Calls. Calls.

1412
01:05:37.224 --> 01:05:40.394
Calls. Calls. Calls. Calls.

1413
01:05:40.561 --> 01:05:42.647
Look at the count.
I guarantee we're gonna go over twenty.

1414
01:05:42.813 --> 01:05:44.482
Those are FTC standards.
Those are legal.

1415
01:05:44.649 --> 01:05:46.984
Those are coming in. Keep your eyes...
Those are actual sales, Joy.

1416
01:05:47.151 --> 01:05:48.361
Lines are busy?

1417
01:05:48.527 --> 01:05:49.987
-Is the queue full?
-MAN: Queue's full.

1418
01:05:50.738 --> 01:05:52.239
Okay. We need a phone call right now.

1419
01:05:52.406 --> 01:05:54.408
When they can't call through,
we gotta keep them watching.

1420
01:05:54.575 --> 01:05:56.077
Did we get a call? Did we get a call?

1421
01:05:56.243 --> 01:05:57.328
Okay. Got it.

1422
01:05:57.495 --> 01:05:58.829
Keep this going. Phone call right now.

1423
01:05:58.913 --> 01:05:59.997
CINDY: Wait, wait, wait!
We have a caller!

1424
01:06:00.039 --> 01:06:01.040
We have a caller!

1425
01:06:01.499 --> 01:06:03.417
Ah, Sharon from Colorado. Hi, Sharon.

1426
01:06:03.584 --> 01:06:04.585
JOAN: Hi, Sharon.

1427
01:06:04.669 --> 01:06:06.963
SHARON (on phone): Cindy and Joan!
I can't believe I'm talking to you!

1428
01:06:07.546 --> 01:06:09.340
CINDY: Are you happy with your necklace?

1429
01:06:09.507 --> 01:06:13.844
SHARON: These necklaces
are so gorgeous and timeless.

1430
01:06:14.011 --> 01:06:15.012
My great-grandmother had things like this.

1431
01:06:15.096 --> 01:06:16.180
Yes, yes. Keep it going.

1432
01:06:16.347 --> 01:06:19.350
I am so excited to have these.

1433
01:06:19.517 --> 01:06:22.728
NEIL: Keep it going. Yes. Yes. Yes.

1434
01:06:22.853 --> 01:06:25.022
CINDY: Get one for your mother.
Get one for your sister.

1435
01:06:25.064 --> 01:06:26.357
NEIL: Watch the counter, Joy. Joy.

1436
01:06:26.524 --> 01:06:28.943
JOAN: You will not regret owning this.
CINDY: No, you will not.

1437
01:06:29.110 --> 01:06:30.277
See those numbers?

1438
01:06:30.444 --> 01:06:32.196
We're gonna wind up at 25,000.

1439
01:06:33.406 --> 01:06:34.865
Cindy knows how to close it.

1440
01:06:35.199 --> 01:06:36.200
Wow.

1441
01:06:37.118 --> 01:06:39.078
Okay, I want you to go home,
I want you to call your lawyer.

1442
01:06:39.245 --> 01:06:40.538
Look at your contract.

1443
01:06:40.705 --> 01:06:43.124
Make sure your product factory
is in line.

1444
01:06:44.417 --> 01:06:46.210
-Okay?
-Okay.

1445
01:06:46.377 --> 01:06:49.213
Okay, Godspeed, good luck.
